1
00:01:35,031 --> 00:01:38,307
? Mon ami Pierrot

2
00:01:38,391 --> 00:01:40,029
? Prête-moi ta plume

3
00:01:40,111 --> 00:01:42,067
? Pour écrire un mot

4
00:01:42,151 --> 00:01:44,107
? Ma chandelle est morte

5
00:01:44,191 --> 00:01:46,147
? Je n'ai plus de feu

6
00:01:46,231 --> 00:01:48,187
? Ouvre-moi ta porte

7
00:01:48,271 --> 00:01:50,227
? Pour l'amour de Dieu

8
00:01:50,311 --> 00:01:52,267
? Ma chandelle est morte

9
00:01:52,351 --> 00:01:54,307
? Je n'ai plus de feu

10
00:01:54,391 --> 00:01:56,347
? Ouvre-moi ta porte

11
00:01:56,431 --> 00:01:58,387
? Pour l'amour de Dieu

12
00:02:02,951 --> 00:02:06,580
? Au jardin de mon pére
les lauriers sont fleuris

13
00:02:07,311 --> 00:02:10,667
? Au jardin de mon pére
les lauriers sont fleuris

14
00:02:13,511 --> 00:02:15,786
- Bonsoir, monsieur.
- Bonsoir, madame.

15
00:02:15,871 --> 00:02:17,623
Combien coûte le cidre là-bas?

16
00:02:17,711 --> 00:02:19,667
- Ça, cidre?
- Oui, oui.

17
00:02:19,751 --> 00:02:23,505
- Cinq francs.
- Oh, c'est trop cher. Bonsoir, monsieur.

18
00:02:23,591 --> 00:02:24,990
Bonsoir, madame.

19
00:02:27,951 --> 00:02:29,623
? Auprés de ma blonde

20
00:02:29,711 --> 00:02:32,020
? Qu'il fait bon fait bon fait bon

21
00:02:32,111 --> 00:02:34,466
? Auprés de ma blonde

22
00:02:38,831 --> 00:02:40,549
Enfin, ma belle.

23
00:02:41,631 --> 00:02:44,509
Let go of me! How dare you, you brutes!
Let go of me.

24
00:02:44,591 --> 00:02:46,229
You didn't get away this time, huh?

25
00:02:46,311 --> 00:02:49,860
- She's English.
- What's she doing here?

26
00:02:49,951 --> 00:02:53,261
- Stealing.
- It's a lie! Keep your dirty hands off me!

27
00:02:53,351 --> 00:02:55,626
How dare you touch me!

28
00:02:55,711 --> 00:02:59,545
I can buy thousands of bottles of your filthy wine.
I'll show you who I am.

29
00:02:59,631 --> 00:03:03,260
Ah, I didn't recognise you. Forgive me, my lady.

30
00:03:03,351 --> 00:03:05,182
My lady is right, you pig.

31
00:03:05,271 --> 00:03:06,624
Qu'est-ce que vous...

32
00:03:11,991 --> 00:03:13,504
(Screams)

33
00:03:27,071 --> 00:03:28,902
Here, dearie, it'll do you good.

34
00:03:36,591 --> 00:03:38,547
Thank you, dear.

35
00:03:38,631 --> 00:03:40,383
You've all been very kind.

36
00:03:41,471 --> 00:03:43,268
I didn't mean to get you into trouble.

37
00:03:43,351 --> 00:03:45,103
No trouble at all.

38
00:03:45,191 --> 00:03:48,467
I always wanted to kick that swine in the pants,
anyhow. I'm glad I done it.

39
00:03:48,551 --> 00:03:50,542
I'm English, too.

40
00:03:50,631 --> 00:03:54,226
My name's Smith - Mary Smith.
What's yours, dearie?

41
00:03:54,311 --> 00:03:56,267
- Emma.
- Emma.

42
00:03:56,351 --> 00:03:59,741
I knew a girl whose name was Emma.
Emily Burrows.

43
00:03:59,831 --> 00:04:01,787
What's yours?

44
00:04:01,871 --> 00:04:03,827
My name?

45
00:04:03,911 --> 00:04:06,266
My name is Emma Lady Hamilton.

46
00:04:07,671 --> 00:04:09,627
Oh...

47
00:04:09,711 --> 00:04:11,667
That's one on me.

48
00:04:11,751 --> 00:04:14,390
It serves me right. I shouldn't be so nosy.

49
00:04:14,471 --> 00:04:17,224
Well, darlin',
if you don't want to tell me your name,

50
00:04:17,311 --> 00:04:20,383
I'd be the last one to poke my nose
in anybody's secrets.

51
00:04:20,471 --> 00:04:26,421
I remember my mother telling me Lady Hamilton
was the most beautiful woman in the world.

52
00:04:28,271 --> 00:04:30,023
Have you got a mirror?

53
00:04:30,111 --> 00:04:31,624
Yes.

54
00:04:33,071 --> 00:04:34,789
Better you didn't, dearie.

55
00:04:35,991 --> 00:04:37,504
Oh, well.

56
00:04:41,511 --> 00:04:43,024
I know it.

57
00:04:43,111 --> 00:04:45,067
I know that face.

58
00:04:45,151 --> 00:04:48,541
For ten years it has looked back at me
from different mirrors.

59
00:04:49,751 --> 00:04:51,503
It must be me.

60
00:04:52,591 --> 00:04:57,585
But I always wait for the miracle,
that one time, just once more,

61
00:04:57,671 --> 00:05:00,424
when it will be another face
that looks at me again.

62
00:05:00,511 --> 00:05:03,105
A face I knew before.

63
00:05:04,711 --> 00:05:06,941
But that face must be dead.

64
00:05:09,551 --> 00:05:11,826
Go on, tell us all about it.

65
00:05:11,911 --> 00:05:14,300
It doesn't matter if it's true or not.

66
00:05:14,391 --> 00:05:16,347
True or not.

67
00:05:17,431 --> 00:05:19,387
I don't know it myself.

68
00:05:19,471 --> 00:05:23,146
It's so long ago, I don't know it anymore.

69
00:05:27,311 --> 00:05:30,508
My life really began when I was 18

70
00:05:33,271 --> 00:05:35,023
I was beautiful then

71
00:05:35,111 --> 00:05:37,067
Coach from London!

72
00:05:37,151 --> 00:05:40,143
One day I arrived in Naples

73
00:05:42,031 --> 00:05:46,309
At the palace of His Excellency
the British Ambassador

74
00:05:46,391 --> 00:05:47,870
How's London, Gavin?

75
00:05:47,951 --> 00:05:51,705
- How's my nephew? Did he send everything?
- It's all here, Your Excellency.

76
00:05:54,751 --> 00:05:56,309
Give me a hand with this chisel!

77
00:05:56,391 --> 00:05:59,940
- Mr Greville sends his regards.
- Don't bother me about Mr Greville now!

78
00:06:00,031 --> 00:06:03,865
- Give me a hammer and chisel.
- It's most important, sir.

79
00:06:15,471 --> 00:06:16,745
Exquisite.

80
00:06:16,831 --> 00:06:18,787
Come and look at this.

81
00:06:22,511 --> 00:06:25,583
- Enchanting. Whose work is it?
- George Romney.

82
00:06:25,671 --> 00:06:28,231
If he could paint reality, he would be a master.

83
00:06:28,311 --> 00:06:30,267
Isn't that reality?

84
00:06:30,351 --> 00:06:33,070
The ideal an artist dreams of.

85
00:06:33,151 --> 00:06:36,985
No woman ever lived with such colouring,
such god-like simplicity.

86
00:06:37,071 --> 00:06:39,027
I thought so too till I met her.

87
00:06:39,111 --> 00:06:40,464
You've met her?

88
00:06:40,551 --> 00:06:44,510
In London, last year. And if you're patient,
you may see her in Naples one day.

89
00:06:44,591 --> 00:06:47,628
- Your Excellency.
- Oh, not now, Gavin. I'll see you presently.

90
00:06:47,711 --> 00:06:49,667
But I must tell you.

91
00:06:49,751 --> 00:06:52,311
Very well, if you must, but tell me quickly.

92
00:07:01,591 --> 00:07:06,142
Mum? Mum? Look, it's lovely.

93
00:07:06,231 --> 00:07:08,028
It's a real palace.

94
00:07:08,111 --> 00:07:09,749
Oh, I do hope Sir William will like us.

95
00:07:09,831 --> 00:07:11,981
Don't worry, darling. Of course he'll like you.

96
00:07:12,071 --> 00:07:15,620
I'll do all the talking. Charlie told me exactly what
to answer to everything.

97
00:07:15,711 --> 00:07:18,748
Why on earth didn't you tell me?
Where are they?

98
00:07:18,831 --> 00:07:20,662
Sshh. Here he comes.

99
00:07:21,951 --> 00:07:24,101
You must forgive me. It's disgraceful.

100
00:07:24,191 --> 00:07:26,307
I'd no idea you'd come.

101
00:07:26,391 --> 00:07:29,542
- How do you do, Miss er...
- Emma Hart, if it pleases Your Excellency.

102
00:07:29,631 --> 00:07:32,304
- How could I forget?
- This is my mother, Your Excellency.

103
00:07:32,391 --> 00:07:36,907
Welcome to Naples, madam.
This is my friend the French Ambassador.

104
00:07:36,991 --> 00:07:38,060
Did you stay in Rome?

105
00:07:38,151 --> 00:07:40,745
Yes, Your Excellency
and thought it very beautiful.

106
00:07:40,831 --> 00:07:44,506
We saw the Colosseum by moonlight
and were deeply impressed by the Vatican.

107
00:07:44,591 --> 00:07:46,582
We just missed the Pope by ten minutes.

108
00:07:46,671 --> 00:07:48,229
That was a great pity, madam.

109
00:07:48,311 --> 00:07:51,189
Did you come through Pisa?
Did you see the famous leaning tower?

110
00:07:51,271 --> 00:07:53,865
Yes, Your Excellency,
and we thought it very beautiful.

111
00:07:53,951 --> 00:07:56,784
We thought the leaning tower of Pisa
one of the most remarkable

112
00:07:56,871 --> 00:07:58,862
and lovely phenomena in the whole of Europe.

113
00:07:58,951 --> 00:08:02,023
A chimney went like that in Liverpool last year
at the soap works.

114
00:08:02,111 --> 00:08:05,990
It leant right over the gin warehouse and
the Bishop said it was the finger of God.

115
00:08:06,071 --> 00:08:09,427
Charles - Mr Greville - sent you
many kind wishes, Your Excellency.

116
00:08:09,511 --> 00:08:11,661
And he hopes I will prove worthy
of your kindness

117
00:08:11,751 --> 00:08:15,107
and speak good French and Italian when
he comes to take me home in October.

118
00:08:15,191 --> 00:08:17,341
He is coming the first week in October.

119
00:08:17,431 --> 00:08:22,186
And er... he sent his uncle... a kiss.

120
00:08:24,191 --> 00:08:27,547
Well, that's the first present I've ever received
from Charles Greville.

121
00:08:27,631 --> 00:08:30,668
I feel sure you must be tired after your journey,
madam.

122
00:08:30,751 --> 00:08:33,265
Francis, show the ladies their rooms.

123
00:08:37,551 --> 00:08:40,429
Au revoir, madam. Au revoir, Miss Hart.

124
00:08:43,991 --> 00:08:46,346
- Who is she?
- Charles Greville found her.

125
00:08:46,431 --> 00:08:48,228
Where can you find things like that?

126
00:08:48,311 --> 00:08:51,621
Charles happened to find her
at Featherstone Castle - Sir Harry's place.

127
00:08:51,711 --> 00:08:54,384
- Oh, she's a relation of Sir Harry?
- You might call her that.

128
00:08:54,471 --> 00:08:58,464
She lived there for a whole hunting season
and a very gay hunting season it was, I'm told.

129
00:08:58,551 --> 00:09:01,111
Oh. And where did Sir Harry find her?

130
00:09:01,191 --> 00:09:05,070
Well, you remember Dr Graham's Temple of Hell
and the famous dance of the seven veils?

131
00:09:05,151 --> 00:09:07,506
- She's a dancer?
- You might call her that.

132
00:09:07,591 --> 00:09:11,425
She was quite a success.
The fewer the veils the greater the success.

133
00:09:11,511 --> 00:09:15,390
But, alas, the police locked the place
just after the last veil fell.

134
00:09:15,471 --> 00:09:18,269
The older I get,
the less I seem to know about women.

135
00:09:18,351 --> 00:09:21,104
It's the penalty of your wicked youth,
Your Excellency.

136
00:09:21,191 --> 00:09:23,421
Don't ask me what happened to her before.

137
00:09:23,511 --> 00:09:25,467
The usual past, I suppose.

138
00:09:25,551 --> 00:09:28,907
A poor little country girl wronged once
and then wronged again.

139
00:09:28,991 --> 00:09:33,507
The old story.
Lower and lower, but always up and up.

140
00:09:33,591 --> 00:09:35,707
And now she's the guest of an ambassador.

141
00:09:35,791 --> 00:09:37,509
With a past like that.

142
00:09:38,591 --> 00:09:39,944
Past?

143
00:09:40,031 --> 00:09:43,910
Look at this statue.
Two hundred years in a Greek temple.

144
00:09:43,991 --> 00:09:46,949
Then thrown into the mud
by some barbarian soldier.

145
00:09:47,031 --> 00:09:51,707
2,000 years sinking lower and lower into the
mud, then dug up by the plough of a peasant,

146
00:09:51,791 --> 00:09:57,024
changing hands every year until at last
it comes to its rightful place.

147
00:09:57,111 --> 00:10:00,786
Into the hands of someone
who understands the glory of its beauty.

148
00:10:00,871 --> 00:10:07,060
Because, my friend, it is still beautiful, isn't it,
despite its past?

149
00:10:07,151 --> 00:10:08,266
Gavin.

150
00:10:08,351 --> 00:10:10,182
I'll dine tonight with Miss Hart

151
00:10:10,271 --> 00:10:12,182
Alone, at eight o'clock.

152
00:10:12,271 --> 00:10:13,909
GAVlN: Yes Your Excellency

153
00:10:13,991 --> 00:10:17,108
Thank you, my man.
I'll ring for you later, if I want you.

154
00:10:17,191 --> 00:10:19,147
Very good, madam.

155
00:10:21,311 --> 00:10:23,267
Two ambassadors, Mum, two!

156
00:10:23,351 --> 00:10:26,184
Well, what did you think of me?
Wasn't I wonderful?

157
00:10:26,311 --> 00:10:27,949
You were all that, darling, and more.

158
00:10:29,031 --> 00:10:30,589
So far, so good.

159
00:10:30,671 --> 00:10:34,903
But, please, Mum, not another word about the
soap factory. Not till I've married Charlie.

160
00:10:34,991 --> 00:10:38,108
Charlie said Sir William was very fussy
about that sort of thing.

161
00:10:38,191 --> 00:10:40,466
Don't worry your pretty head
about Sir William.

162
00:10:40,551 --> 00:10:43,304
You'll have him eating out of your hand
within three months.

163
00:10:43,391 --> 00:10:46,667
Three months? Three days?
He'll be eating out of it tonight.

164
00:10:46,751 --> 00:10:48,423
And in a month,

165
00:10:48,511 --> 00:10:50,706
Charlie will be here to take us home.

166
00:10:50,791 --> 00:10:52,861
How pleased he'll be with me.

167
00:10:52,951 --> 00:10:54,987
He will indeed, but there's no great hurry.

168
00:10:55,071 --> 00:10:57,983
It's very nice here just now
and it's not costing us a farthing.

169
00:10:58,071 --> 00:11:02,223
It's all very well for you, but what about me?
''Yes, Your Excellency. No, Your Excellency.

170
00:11:02,311 --> 00:11:04,108
Of course, Your Excellency.''

171
00:11:04,191 --> 00:11:07,069
- Oh, how I miss my Charlie.
- Yes, he's a likely, young fellow.

172
00:11:07,151 --> 00:11:10,860
Burt there's no-one good enough for my Emily,
though it's her own mother who says so.

173
00:11:10,951 --> 00:11:15,229
But, Mother, I wouldn't exist without Charlie.
He's done everything for me, everything.

174
00:11:15,311 --> 00:11:17,267
Well, he's... made me a lady.

175
00:11:17,351 --> 00:11:19,069
I know, darling, I know.

176
00:11:19,151 --> 00:11:21,949
Oh! Look at that mountain
with the smoke coming out of it.

177
00:11:22,031 --> 00:11:25,182
The coachman said it went off a few years ago
and killed several people.

178
00:11:25,271 --> 00:11:26,943
That would never happen in Liverpool.

179
00:11:27,031 --> 00:11:30,819
Oh, Mother, you're hopeless. That's a famous
volcano. People come miles to see it.

180
00:11:30,911 --> 00:11:33,471
What do they call it? Charles told me 100 times.

181
00:11:33,631 --> 00:11:36,748
Smoking mountain. Vesuvius, that's it, Vesuvius.

182
00:11:36,831 --> 00:11:39,868
If Sir William asks you what you think
of it, just say it's lovely.

183
00:11:39,951 --> 00:11:42,988
- Yes, dear.
- It's mixed up with the history of Ancient Rome.

184
00:11:43,071 --> 00:11:45,744
Nero set it on fire and said the Christians did it.

185
00:11:45,831 --> 00:11:50,507
Remember, Mother, it's knowing little things
like that that makes you a lady.

186
00:11:50,591 --> 00:11:52,547
(String quartet plays minuet)

187
00:12:22,831 --> 00:12:26,790
Whenever I have a nice piece of fish,
it always makes me think of the sea.

188
00:12:26,871 --> 00:12:28,702
- The what?
- The sea Your Excellency

189
00:12:28,791 --> 00:12:29,860
Oh, yes.

190
00:12:29,951 --> 00:12:32,511
Charles was wonderful about things like that.

191
00:12:32,591 --> 00:12:34,627
- About fish?
- Oh!

192
00:12:34,711 --> 00:12:36,702
You're so funny, Your Excellency.

193
00:12:36,791 --> 00:12:40,067
Every time you call me ''Your Excellency'',
it adds one year to my life.

194
00:12:40,151 --> 00:12:42,267
- Sir William?
- That's getting better

195
00:12:42,351 --> 00:12:46,390
Tell me, my dear.
Was my nephew so positive about coming here?

196
00:12:46,471 --> 00:12:50,749
Oh, absolutely. He would have brought me here
himself, if he hadn't been detained in London.

197
00:12:50,831 --> 00:12:53,026
Just a second, my dear.

198
00:12:53,111 --> 00:12:55,420
As we're to live together under the same roof

199
00:12:55,511 --> 00:12:59,504
I see no reason why we should not
be perfectly frank with one another

200
00:13:04,791 --> 00:13:09,865
As much as I hate to spoil this beautiful picture
that you have drawn for yourseIf of my nephew,

201
00:13:09,951 --> 00:13:12,704
there's one point that must be made quite clear.

202
00:13:12,791 --> 00:13:15,669
Charles Greville will never come to Naples

203
00:13:16,831 --> 00:13:21,586
But, Your Excellency, Uncle,
he definitely promised.

204
00:13:21,671 --> 00:13:25,869
There is a wide gap between my nephew's
promises and his fulfilment of them

205
00:13:25,951 --> 00:13:28,909
The promise he gave me, he will keep.

206
00:13:30,071 --> 00:13:33,029
Your confidence in him is really touching.

207
00:13:34,631 --> 00:13:36,462
Did he promise you marriage as well?

208
00:13:37,551 --> 00:13:40,702
Why deny it? It must be written all over me.

209
00:13:40,791 --> 00:13:44,067
I'm afraid I've got to destroy
those sweet dreams of yours.

210
00:13:44,151 --> 00:13:47,826
My nephew never had the slightest intention
of marrying you.

211
00:13:47,911 --> 00:13:50,948
Either with my consent or without it.

212
00:13:53,631 --> 00:13:55,940
What did you say, Your Excellency?

213
00:13:57,311 --> 00:14:00,986
I said he's not going to marry you, Emma.

214
00:14:03,911 --> 00:14:05,822
But that's not possible.

215
00:14:06,951 --> 00:14:09,181
Why should he send me here with my mother?

216
00:14:09,271 --> 00:14:11,227
It costs a lot of money, the journey.

217
00:14:11,311 --> 00:14:15,748
Perhaps he feIt you would be better off
with his uncle. A nice vacation.

218
00:14:15,831 --> 00:14:17,787
But I didn't need a vacation.

219
00:14:17,871 --> 00:14:21,181
No. No, there must be something else.

220
00:14:22,231 --> 00:14:25,462
And what's to happen after the vacation,
if he doesn't want to marry me?

221
00:14:25,551 --> 00:14:28,941
He's talked of nothing else for years.
It was his idea. I never urged him.

222
00:14:29,031 --> 00:14:31,181
I was quite happy with him just as it was.

223
00:14:33,071 --> 00:14:36,825
Tell me, Your Excellency,
but please tell me the truth.

224
00:14:37,911 --> 00:14:40,141
Did Charles tell you about me?

225
00:14:40,231 --> 00:14:42,187
Do you know about my

226
00:14:42,271 --> 00:14:46,549
He did. And I imagine that was the only thing
he did not lie about.

227
00:14:50,951 --> 00:14:53,749
Oh but please my dear,
I don't want to make you feel ashamed.

228
00:14:53,831 --> 00:14:57,710
Ashamed? Oh, I'm not ashamed.
There's nothing to be ashamed of.

229
00:14:57,791 --> 00:15:01,227
It's true there were men in my life
before Charles, I admit it.

230
00:15:01,311 --> 00:15:03,586
I made mistakes, I was young, I was stupid.

231
00:15:03,671 --> 00:15:05,707
I believed in men and their promises.

232
00:15:05,791 --> 00:15:08,351
Charles knew about me
before he took me into the house,

233
00:15:08,431 --> 00:15:10,069
before he promised to marry me.

234
00:15:10,151 --> 00:15:13,826
And now I'm different, not only my clothes,
but inside.

235
00:15:13,911 --> 00:15:16,300
I'm good. I know I'm good.

236
00:15:16,391 --> 00:15:18,347
So why should he lie to me?

237
00:15:18,431 --> 00:15:21,229
Why did he send me here?
What am I doing here?

238
00:15:21,311 --> 00:15:23,586
Charles had a lot of debts. Did you know that?

239
00:15:23,671 --> 00:15:25,423
Yes, quite a lot, I know.

240
00:15:25,511 --> 00:15:28,867
His debts have been paid to the tune of £5,000.

241
00:15:28,951 --> 00:15:33,308
Besides he has plenty of cash
to save him from new debts for a long time

242
00:15:38,911 --> 00:15:40,663
Oh, I see.

243
00:15:42,471 --> 00:15:44,427
see

244
00:15:45,111 --> 00:15:53,029
He sold you antiques, paintings, and among
the bric-a-brac, a certain Emma Hart.

245
00:15:54,791 --> 00:15:58,306
(Sobs) That wasn't fair.
That wasn't gentlemanlike.

246
00:15:58,391 --> 00:16:01,781
He shouldn't have raised me up
just to throw me down again.

247
00:16:01,871 --> 00:16:03,065
My dear.

248
00:16:03,151 --> 00:16:04,948
Leave me alone. You're just as bad as he is.

249
00:16:05,031 --> 00:16:07,909
Perhaps you haven't made
such a good bargain after all.

250
00:16:07,991 --> 00:16:09,344
I'm not going to stay here.

251
00:16:09,431 --> 00:16:11,899
I'm going away now. Now!

252
00:16:13,991 --> 00:16:15,947
(Sobs)

253
00:16:20,191 --> 00:16:22,022
Oh, don't take it to heart, my dear.

254
00:16:22,111 --> 00:16:25,342
Forget Charles, forget the old memories,
forget London.

255
00:16:25,431 --> 00:16:28,309
I can offer you a new life
and a far more exciting one.

256
00:16:28,391 --> 00:16:30,347
Naples is a wonderful city.

257
00:16:30,431 --> 00:16:33,150
You'll be a success here. You'll like it.

258
00:16:33,231 --> 00:16:36,143
Perhaps not today, nor even tomorrow.

259
00:16:36,231 --> 00:16:39,303
But you are young and the young heal quickly.

260
00:16:44,951 --> 00:16:48,387
You will learn singing and music
under the greatest masters in Italy.

261
00:16:48,471 --> 00:16:51,588
You will speak French and Italian
with our finest teachers.

262
00:16:51,671 --> 00:16:54,788
Everyone of account in Europe comes to my
house. You will meet them all.

263
00:16:54,871 --> 00:16:57,908
You will dine with famous soldiers,
artists and statesmen.

264
00:16:57,991 --> 00:17:02,507
You can't be presented at court, of course,
but you will have a villa by the sea and a coach.

265
00:17:02,591 --> 00:17:04,946
You will have your private box at the opera.

266
00:17:05,031 --> 00:17:08,501
Ever since I first saw you in London,
I feIt this house of mine to be empty,

267
00:17:08,591 --> 00:17:11,230
missing its greatest and most lovely ornament.

268
00:17:11,311 --> 00:17:13,381
You will be that ornament, my dear.

269
00:17:13,471 --> 00:17:16,224
And except for that absurd presentation at court,

270
00:17:16,311 --> 00:17:20,190
you will have everything in life
that a woman could possibly dream of.

271
00:17:22,511 --> 00:17:23,910
What did you say?

272
00:17:23,991 --> 00:17:25,743
Nothing. Try to sleep.

273
00:17:26,951 --> 00:17:28,748
Goodnight, Emma.

274
00:17:35,391 --> 00:17:37,951
MOTHER: What's wrong, darling?

275
00:17:38,031 --> 00:17:39,384
Oh, mum!

276
00:17:39,471 --> 00:17:41,427
Dear, dear.

277
00:17:41,511 --> 00:17:43,467
(Sobs) Mum, I'm so miserable.

278
00:17:45,111 --> 00:17:47,579
- What's wrong?
- He never wanted to marry me.

279
00:17:47,671 --> 00:17:52,665
He got £5,000 from the old man
to send me here.

280
00:17:53,711 --> 00:17:55,747
He never wanted to marry me.

281
00:17:55,831 --> 00:17:59,062
Don't cry, my sweet.
You're too good for any of them.

282
00:17:59,151 --> 00:18:00,504
I'm going to pack now.

283
00:18:00,591 --> 00:18:05,619
We'll go right back to London and you can give
that precious Mr Greville a piece of your mind.

284
00:18:05,711 --> 00:18:10,102
Plenty of good men want to marry my Emily.
There, now, darling. Don't cry.

285
00:18:10,191 --> 00:18:13,342
There's just as good fish in the sea
as ever came out of it.

286
00:18:13,431 --> 00:18:16,264
(Emma Sobs)
Darling, precious Emily, there, now.

287
00:18:19,031 --> 00:18:21,670
EMMA: And I forgot London
and the old memories.

288
00:18:21,751 --> 00:18:24,982
I was young I healed quickly.

289
00:18:25,951 --> 00:18:29,227
I learnt French, Italian, singing, and music.

290
00:18:30,271 --> 00:18:33,388
One day I had more than I ever dreamed of.

291
00:18:33,471 --> 00:18:36,986
I became his wife - Emma Lady Hamilton.

292
00:18:49,871 --> 00:18:51,827
(Singing)

293
00:18:53,951 --> 00:18:56,146
Sshh!

294
00:18:56,231 --> 00:18:58,665
My daughter, Her Ladyship, is still asleep.

295
00:18:58,751 --> 00:19:00,662
- Good morning, Contessa.
- Good morning.

296
00:19:00,751 --> 00:19:05,029
My daughter, Her Ladyship, is still resting.
Perhaps you wouldn't mind waiting a little while.

297
00:19:05,111 --> 00:19:09,070
- How was Her Majesty this morning?
- Her cold is troublesome. Her throat is sore.

298
00:19:09,151 --> 00:19:10,709
- Has it gone out of her nose?
-No.

299
00:19:10,791 --> 00:19:15,103
The best way to cure a sore throat
is to wrap a woollen sock at night, going to bed.

300
00:19:15,191 --> 00:19:17,864
- Oh?
- Good morning. Good morning, Contessa.

301
00:19:17,951 --> 00:19:19,430
Good morning, Your Excellency.

302
00:19:19,511 --> 00:19:21,661
- Is Emma still asleep?
- She is asleep.

303
00:19:21,751 --> 00:19:25,790
In my village, a husband just turns round in bed
and looks for himseIf to know.

304
00:19:25,871 --> 00:19:29,546
Yes, and the Queen of Naples does not wear
woollen socks to pin around her throat.

305
00:19:29,631 --> 00:19:34,022
If the Queen of Naples wore a hefty pair of
woollen socks, she wouldn't have a sore throat.

306
00:19:34,631 --> 00:19:36,587
(Explosion outside)

307
00:19:39,031 --> 00:19:40,020
(Explosion)

308
00:19:40,111 --> 00:19:42,944
- What's happened?
- I don't know.

309
00:19:43,031 --> 00:19:44,623
(Explosion)

310
00:19:45,671 --> 00:19:48,026
Maybe the smoking mountain went off again.

311
00:19:49,071 --> 00:19:51,426
Let's see. Come along.

312
00:19:54,471 --> 00:19:56,427
(Explosions continue)

313
00:19:58,471 --> 00:20:00,427
(Explosion)

314
00:20:04,911 --> 00:20:06,549
How wonderful! A battleship.

315
00:20:12,911 --> 00:20:16,347
You should see the Queen about this.
Salutes at this hour of the morning.

316
00:20:16,431 --> 00:20:19,867
Why shouldn't they blow their cannons off?
That's what they've got them for.

317
00:20:19,951 --> 00:20:21,020
Boom!

318
00:20:24,671 --> 00:20:26,627
- Boom!
- Good morning, my dear.

319
00:20:26,711 --> 00:20:28,667
Boom! Good morning, William.

320
00:20:28,751 --> 00:20:31,106
Here, give it to me.

321
00:20:37,591 --> 00:20:39,980
? Rule Britannia

322
00:20:40,071 --> 00:20:42,027
Let me look, my dear.

323
00:20:45,791 --> 00:20:47,668
There's a small boat coming ashore.

324
00:20:47,751 --> 00:20:50,868
They will probably need me.
Excuse me, my dear.

325
00:21:02,111 --> 00:21:04,466
- The mail is just in, Emma.
- I'll attend to it later.

326
00:21:04,551 --> 00:21:06,382
Here's a nice fat one from London.

327
00:21:06,471 --> 00:21:07,745
Oh.

328
00:21:07,831 --> 00:21:11,665
(Reads) Her Excellency, Emma Lady Hamilton,
British Embassy, Naples.

329
00:21:13,431 --> 00:21:15,023
Charles Greville, London.

330
00:21:15,111 --> 00:21:17,067
Open it, child, open it.

331
00:21:17,151 --> 00:21:21,941
I think not. Send it back
and write on it, ''Unopened. Return to sender''.

332
00:21:22,031 --> 00:21:25,228
Poor Charles. He's exactly three years too late.

333
00:21:25,311 --> 00:21:28,303
And as far as I'm concerned,
he simply doesn't exist.

334
00:21:30,751 --> 00:21:32,707
Are you happy, my child?

335
00:21:33,471 --> 00:21:35,223
Happy?

336
00:21:35,311 --> 00:21:39,827
Three years ago, my only idea of happiness
was to be married to Charles Greville.

337
00:21:40,871 --> 00:21:42,827
After that, I wanted revenge.

338
00:21:43,991 --> 00:21:45,947
Well, I got that in a way, too.

339
00:21:46,991 --> 00:21:49,061
Then I wanted to be presented at court.

340
00:21:49,151 --> 00:21:51,824
And even that impossible wish was granted
to me.

341
00:21:53,551 --> 00:21:55,507
I've got everything.

342
00:21:55,591 --> 00:21:58,742
Everything a woman of the world
could possibly wish for.

343
00:21:59,471 --> 00:22:01,348
So why shouldn't I be happy?

344
00:22:01,431 --> 00:22:03,626
Of course, I'm happy, Mother.

345
00:22:03,711 --> 00:22:06,623
Well, Emma, what's good enough for you
is good enough for me.

346
00:22:06,711 --> 00:22:09,783
And being mother to Her Ladyship
is not to be sneezed at either.

347
00:22:09,871 --> 00:22:11,748
(Laughs)
- You silly old thing.

348
00:22:11,831 --> 00:22:14,299
You're lovely, Emma.
You're so beautiful, Emma.

349
00:22:14,391 --> 00:22:18,907
And what about you? Look at you with
your little cap and your silver buttons.

350
00:22:18,991 --> 00:22:21,346
And your beautiful skirt.

351
00:22:21,431 --> 00:22:23,387
You're the beautiful one.

352
00:22:23,471 --> 00:22:25,939
Your Ladyship,
could you spare me a moment, please?

353
00:22:26,031 --> 00:22:27,623
Yes, Gavin. I'm in a great hurry.

354
00:22:27,711 --> 00:22:30,544
It's about the dinner invitations for Sunday night.

355
00:22:30,631 --> 00:22:34,340
Then, of course, His Eminence the Archbishop,
the Duchess of Argyle,

356
00:22:34,431 --> 00:22:37,389
and if there's no performance
the Prima Donna of the San Carlo.

357
00:22:37,471 --> 00:22:40,190
- And the two ladies - which is deaf?
- The Contessa Giovanni.

358
00:22:40,271 --> 00:22:41,829
We put her on Sir William's right.

359
00:22:41,911 --> 00:22:44,869
Marquess Compiani the old harpy,
and the French Ambassador -

360
00:22:44,951 --> 00:22:46,623
we'll put him there between them.

361
00:22:46,711 --> 00:22:48,110
Oh, he'll have a nice time.

362
00:22:48,191 --> 00:22:52,309
Beg pardon, My Lady, but Sir William informs
me the French Ambassador cannot be invited.

363
00:22:53,191 --> 00:22:55,147
- Why ever not?
- Sir William mentioned

364
00:22:55,231 --> 00:22:59,861
Sir William mentioned... Sir William mentioned
there's a difference between the er...

365
00:22:59,951 --> 00:23:02,909
William, what's this absurd business
about the French Ambassador?

366
00:23:02,991 --> 00:23:04,788
l need him for the party on Sunday night.

367
00:23:04,871 --> 00:23:07,590
My dear, may I introduce
the captain of the Agamemnon?

368
00:23:07,671 --> 00:23:09,389
How do you do? But William, I need him.

369
00:23:09,471 --> 00:23:13,305
He's amusing and he's a bachelor and I need
a single man to make my number even.

370
00:23:13,391 --> 00:23:17,430
I'm sorry, my dear, but we won't be seeing
the French Ambassador for quite some time.

371
00:23:17,511 --> 00:23:19,069
Why? What's the matter with him?

372
00:23:19,151 --> 00:23:20,903
The captain can explain that.

373
00:23:20,991 --> 00:23:23,186
- He has a message.
- We're at war with France.

374
00:23:23,271 --> 00:23:26,627
War? That's torn it.
Bang goes the French Ambassador.

375
00:23:26,711 --> 00:23:31,307
Oh, dear. Who can I get to sit between
these two dreary old ladies?

376
00:23:35,391 --> 00:23:39,782
My dear captain, we shall be so delighted
if you will dine with us on Sunday night.

377
00:23:39,871 --> 00:23:43,181
You will sit between the two most amusing
and charming ladies in Naples.

378
00:23:43,271 --> 00:23:45,148
You're very kind, but I sail tonight.

379
00:23:45,231 --> 00:23:47,301
Oh, then I gather you must be in a hurry.

380
00:23:47,391 --> 00:23:50,508
Don't let me disturb your conference. I'm going.

381
00:23:52,751 --> 00:23:56,710
Well, Captain, you were saying
that the Admiral of the Fleet wanted...

382
00:23:56,791 --> 00:23:58,270
Yes, sir.

383
00:24:00,271 --> 00:24:02,865
Lord Hood advised me to instruct you...

384
00:24:04,951 --> 00:24:08,580
It's all right, Captain,
I have no secrets from Lady Hamilton.

385
00:24:08,671 --> 00:24:10,946
I'm very sorry, Sir William. You must forgive me.

386
00:24:11,031 --> 00:24:14,307
I'm not used to discussing matters of this kind
in the presence of ladies.

387
00:24:14,391 --> 00:24:17,303
Oh. Is it as wicked as all that? Good gracious.

388
00:24:17,391 --> 00:24:19,029
I promised to be with the Queen at 1 2.

389
00:24:19,111 --> 00:24:22,581
She won't order a single new dress
until I've discussed the patterns with her.

390
00:24:22,671 --> 00:24:24,866
That's a very great responsibility, my dear.

391
00:24:24,951 --> 00:24:26,907
- Goodbye, William.
- Goodbye.

392
00:24:32,031 --> 00:24:33,828
We've captured Toulon.

393
00:24:33,911 --> 00:24:37,699
The Admiral needs 10 000 troops to hold it
It would take three weeks from England

394
00:24:37,791 --> 00:24:39,861
From here, they should be in Toulon in two
days.

395
00:24:39,951 --> 00:24:43,023
The treaty between England and Naples
provides full co-operation

396
00:24:43,111 --> 00:24:46,387
and the Admiral expects you to secure those
troops from the King of Naples.

397
00:24:46,471 --> 00:24:48,666
I'll apply for an audience with the King.

398
00:24:48,751 --> 00:24:52,630
But surely in a matter as urgent as this,
we could see the King at once.

399
00:24:52,711 --> 00:24:56,067
At once? I can't just walk into the Royal Palace.

400
00:24:56,151 --> 00:24:58,904
Well, when will you get the audience?

401
00:24:58,991 --> 00:25:01,505
Friday may be possible.
Saturday almost certain.

402
00:25:01,591 --> 00:25:03,946
But we must have these troops immediately.

403
00:25:04,031 --> 00:25:08,468
You must leave this in my hands.
You see, I know these people and you don't.

404
00:25:08,551 --> 00:25:10,507
I'll make out the application at once.

405
00:25:27,071 --> 00:25:29,027
EMMA: Yes, that's me too.

406
00:25:30,551 --> 00:25:32,348
Do you like it? It's a Romney.

407
00:25:32,431 --> 00:25:34,865
Circe watching her lover sail away.

408
00:25:36,351 --> 00:25:37,500
Is it?

409
00:25:37,591 --> 00:25:41,186
You know, I could get you those troops like that.

410
00:25:41,271 --> 00:25:46,664
You were speaking rather loudly, Captain, and
the houses get so stuffy if you close the doors.

411
00:25:46,751 --> 00:25:50,061
You're worried, aren't you?
You have an important mission, haven't you?

412
00:25:50,151 --> 00:25:53,427
Has it ever occurred to you that women can
sometimes be of more help than men?

413
00:25:53,511 --> 00:25:55,422
Not in a matter of this kind, Lady Hamilton.

414
00:25:55,511 --> 00:25:56,705
How do you know?

415
00:25:56,791 --> 00:26:01,581
It just happens that I shall be seeing the Queen
within the next ten minutes.

416
00:26:01,671 --> 00:26:04,981
The Queen? This is an important matter of state.

417
00:26:05,071 --> 00:26:07,585
All the more reason to see the Queen.

418
00:26:09,031 --> 00:26:11,101
Now I'll let you into a secret, Captain.

419
00:26:11,191 --> 00:26:13,147
Which everyone in Europe knows.

420
00:26:13,231 --> 00:26:14,789
Except you, Captain.

421
00:26:14,871 --> 00:26:18,341
The real King of Naples is the Queen.

422
00:26:18,431 --> 00:26:20,626
E licenziata, hai capito?

423
00:26:20,711 --> 00:26:23,271
(The children's chatter drowns her out)

424
00:26:28,031 --> 00:26:31,341
Her Majesty is pleased
to be with her children this hour.

425
00:26:31,431 --> 00:26:34,104
But my orders are to let My Lady in any time.

426
00:26:34,191 --> 00:26:39,584
Even if the princes and princesses please
to be with their august parents.

427
00:26:39,671 --> 00:26:41,866
The august family appears to be pretty big.

428
00:26:41,951 --> 00:26:45,068
The marriage of the august parents
is continuously blessed.

429
00:26:45,151 --> 00:26:48,826
There are 15 princes and princesses so far.
You will see.

430
00:26:48,911 --> 00:26:50,867
(Pandemonium)

431
00:26:51,191 --> 00:26:53,147
Lady Hamilton!

432
00:27:22,991 --> 00:27:24,947
(Dog barks)

433
00:27:37,071 --> 00:27:39,301
(Pandemonium drowns out conversation)

434
00:27:40,951 --> 00:27:44,421
''I have the honour to be etc, etc, etc.''
And I'll sign it at once.

435
00:27:45,231 --> 00:27:46,425
Phew!

436
00:27:58,151 --> 00:28:01,905
Here we are, Captain. I'll have this application
to the palace in haIf an hour.

437
00:28:01,991 --> 00:28:05,870
I thought it advisable to ask for only 8,000 men.
We may get as many as 5,000.

438
00:28:05,951 --> 00:28:09,910
We asked for 20,000 and we got 1 0,000. There.

439
00:28:12,231 --> 00:28:14,267
I'm very much indebted to Lady Hamilton

440
00:28:14,351 --> 00:28:17,582
Her campaign against the Queen
was a masterpiece of strategy.

441
00:28:17,671 --> 00:28:20,981
Well, there, my dear captain,
you see the real Ambassador to Naples.

442
00:28:21,071 --> 00:28:22,823
At least to the Queen of Naples.

443
00:28:22,911 --> 00:28:26,824
Captain, now that you have your soldiers,
there's no need for you to leave so soon.

444
00:28:26,911 --> 00:28:30,028
You can go tomorrow. We'll have a wonderful
party on your ship tonight.

445
00:28:30,111 --> 00:28:34,548
I'll bring the Queen and you'll get the King if
you'll allow him to conduct the ship's orchestra.

446
00:28:34,631 --> 00:28:38,180
We'll sail out to Capri.
By midnight, we'll be at the Blue Grotto.

447
00:28:38,271 --> 00:28:42,389
Capri by moonlight.
You've no idea how beautiful the world can be.

448
00:28:42,471 --> 00:28:47,340
We'll decorate the ship with flowers. And I'll
dance. I expect you've heard of my dances.

449
00:28:47,431 --> 00:28:50,070
The Dance Of The Nymph
goes beautifully with a night on a ship

450
00:28:50,151 --> 00:28:55,225
I'll wear a long tunic of pale blue cashmere.

451
00:28:56,031 --> 00:28:59,068
No high coiffure. Just loose hair.

452
00:28:59,151 --> 00:29:02,621
Like a Greek Goddess Gavin we're to have
a party on the battleship tonight

453
00:29:02,711 --> 00:29:05,225
Get out the Chinese lanterns
to send to the harbour.

454
00:29:05,311 --> 00:29:08,144
And ask the chef to make big steak pies,
100 of them.

455
00:29:08,231 --> 00:29:11,428
And get some rum for the sailors.
It is rum they drink, isn't it, Captain?

456
00:29:11,511 --> 00:29:13,547
It will be magnificent, stupendous.

457
00:29:13,631 --> 00:29:16,065
- Won't I be wonderful, William?
- You will.

458
00:29:16,151 --> 00:29:20,064
I'm sorry to be ungallant, but I've just been
summoned to weigh anchor immediately.

459
00:29:20,151 --> 00:29:24,383
May I present my son,
midshipman on the Agamemnon?

460
00:29:24,471 --> 00:29:26,109
Such a big son.

461
00:29:26,191 --> 00:29:28,341
- My step-son.
-Your wife lives in England?

462
00:29:28,431 --> 00:29:29,944
Yes, sir, in Norfolk.

463
00:29:30,031 --> 00:29:32,784
And this young man is your chaperone.

464
00:29:32,871 --> 00:29:35,021
Precisely. He keeps a good watch on me.

465
00:29:35,111 --> 00:29:37,545
- Goodbye, Sir William.
- Goodbye, Captain.

466
00:29:37,631 --> 00:29:39,030
Goodbye, Lady Hamilton.

467
00:29:39,111 --> 00:29:41,545
May I say,
you've done good service for your country?

468
00:29:41,631 --> 00:29:45,863
It's been rather fun, hasn't it? If you're passing
Naples again, I hope you'll come and see us.

469
00:29:45,951 --> 00:29:50,308
And next time, there's no need to blow off
your cannons, just knock at the door.

470
00:29:50,391 --> 00:29:51,506
Goodbye.

471
00:29:51,591 --> 00:29:53,149
What was your name?

472
00:29:53,231 --> 00:29:54,823
Nelson.

473
00:29:59,351 --> 00:30:03,981
William, did I seem very silly,
talking about the party in the moonlight?

474
00:30:04,071 --> 00:30:06,027
Silly? Of course, my dear.

475
00:30:06,111 --> 00:30:08,989
But delightfully silly. My Emma at her best.

476
00:30:09,071 --> 00:30:10,868
I wonder.

477
00:30:10,951 --> 00:30:12,907
He was so serious.

478
00:30:12,991 --> 00:30:15,141
All of a sudden, I began to feel foolish.

479
00:30:15,231 --> 00:30:19,782
I don't think a woman can be at her best,
playing the fool with news of war.

480
00:30:19,871 --> 00:30:21,429
Don't think about it, my dear.

481
00:30:21,511 --> 00:30:25,026
War is a sordid, ugly thing,
so there's no need for them to bother you.

482
00:30:25,111 --> 00:30:27,147
My Lady, your dancing master's here.

483
00:30:27,231 --> 00:30:29,791
- Shall I show him to the dancing room?
-No, send him away.

484
00:30:29,871 --> 00:30:32,101
- But, Emma.
- I don't feel like dancing.

485
00:30:32,191 --> 00:30:35,581
William, you've left certain gaps in my
education. This war, for instance.

486
00:30:35,671 --> 00:30:37,548
- I know nothing about it.
- But my dear...

487
00:30:37,631 --> 00:30:40,782
Every time I ask you a serious question,
you begin shuffling about.

488
00:30:40,871 --> 00:30:42,827
Tell me about it. How did it happen?

489
00:30:42,911 --> 00:30:46,665
- It's very dull, my dear.
- I don't care how dull it is. I want to know.

490
00:30:46,751 --> 00:30:48,309
Well...

491
00:30:48,391 --> 00:30:49,949
here's England.

492
00:30:52,071 --> 00:30:53,709
Such a tiny little bit.

493
00:30:53,791 --> 00:30:55,144
Where are we?

494
00:30:55,231 --> 00:30:57,825
Here at Naples.

495
00:30:57,911 --> 00:30:59,390
But why should England fight?

496
00:30:59,471 --> 00:31:03,430
Because all through these centuries,
she has built up a commonwealth,

497
00:31:03,511 --> 00:31:07,663
in which every little spot has its purpose
and value to the balance line of life.

498
00:31:07,751 --> 00:31:11,949
And there are always men,
who for the sake of their insane ambition,

499
00:31:12,031 --> 00:31:14,261
want to destroy what other people build.

500
00:31:14,351 --> 00:31:18,424
And therefore, this tiny little bit,
as you call it, Emma,

501
00:31:18,511 --> 00:31:24,381
has to send out its ships again and again to fight
those who want to dictate their will to others.

502
00:31:25,711 --> 00:31:27,667
EMMA: Then came five years of war

503
00:31:28,871 --> 00:31:30,827
We fought alone with no allies

504
00:31:31,911 --> 00:31:35,142
The whole of Europe in deadly fear
of Napoleon Bonaparte

505
00:31:36,391 --> 00:31:40,350
Nothing between him and the conquest
of the world but a few ships

506
00:31:45,471 --> 00:31:47,143
And Nelson

507
00:31:47,231 --> 00:31:50,303
MAN: His Majesty is pleased to award you
the Knighthood of the Bath

508
00:31:50,391 --> 00:31:53,383
and you are promoted to Rear Admiral
of the Blue

509
00:31:53,471 --> 00:31:56,543
Sir Horatio, that's wonderful.
The men will be delighted.

510
00:31:56,631 --> 00:31:58,110
Oh, yes.

511
00:31:58,191 --> 00:32:02,150
We'll catch Bonaparte in a week,
if we have an extra button on our coat tails.

512
00:32:02,231 --> 00:32:06,747
Five years of this war and gentlemen in London
think that men can go on without water or food.

513
00:32:06,831 --> 00:32:08,947
And I can fight the enemy without ammunition.

514
00:32:09,031 --> 00:32:13,183
Even His Excellency the Ambassador here
sees fit to ignore our plight.

515
00:32:13,271 --> 00:32:14,784
What's the matter with the lamp?

516
00:32:14,871 --> 00:32:17,305
It's nearly empty, sir. No more oil on board.

517
00:32:18,991 --> 00:32:21,107
Well, turn it down.

518
00:32:22,551 --> 00:32:24,621
NELSON: Hardy?
- Yes, sir.

519
00:32:24,711 --> 00:32:26,190
Sir Horatio from now on, sir.

520
00:32:26,271 --> 00:32:28,227
Oh, not to you, Hardy.

521
00:32:28,311 --> 00:32:30,666
Captain always, I hope.

522
00:32:30,751 --> 00:32:33,424
Captain or Sir Horatio,
I can't stand this any longer.

523
00:32:33,511 --> 00:32:35,149
What's Sir William Hamilton doing?

524
00:32:35,231 --> 00:32:37,870
Why don't we sail up to Naples
and blow 'em out of their beds?

525
00:32:37,951 --> 00:32:39,907
They'd give us water and meat then.

526
00:32:39,991 --> 00:32:43,028
- Do you expect me to fire at a neutral port?
- Neutral?

527
00:32:43,111 --> 00:32:45,067
Neutral against England?

528
00:32:45,151 --> 00:32:48,826
Yes. Things were different when we were here
five years ago, weren't they?

529
00:32:48,911 --> 00:32:51,061
Our braid was shining in those days.

530
00:32:51,151 --> 00:32:54,905
Today they won't even let us anchor
in the harbour as though we had the plague.

531
00:32:54,991 --> 00:32:58,506
They're so scared of Bonaparte,
they daren't help the people who fight him.

532
00:32:59,551 --> 00:33:00,950
Starboard!

533
00:33:07,311 --> 00:33:09,347
What a wonderful way to get upstairs.

534
00:33:14,791 --> 00:33:16,543
How exciting.

535
00:33:17,991 --> 00:33:19,663
At last I'm on a battleship.

536
00:33:19,751 --> 00:33:22,026
NELSON: Trowbridge, did you get anything?

537
00:33:22,111 --> 00:33:23,829
Sir, there is someone here with me.

538
00:33:23,911 --> 00:33:26,345
- The Ambassador.
- No sir Lady Hamilton

539
00:33:26,431 --> 00:33:28,865
Is there no light? I can't see anything.

540
00:33:28,951 --> 00:33:30,907
Everything's so dark.

541
00:33:30,991 --> 00:33:33,425
Where's Horatio?

542
00:33:33,511 --> 00:33:35,581
Turn up the lamp Josiah

543
00:33:38,351 --> 00:33:40,660
NELSON: How is Sir William? Ill, I presume?

544
00:33:41,711 --> 00:33:45,101
You must please forgive me
if I seem a little abrupt.

545
00:33:45,191 --> 00:33:48,627
We've been living here under great difficulties.
No food or fresh water.

546
00:33:48,711 --> 00:33:50,303
No rum no tobacco

547
00:33:50,391 --> 00:33:55,146
The Neapolitans have forgotten that they're our
allies and that we're fighting for their cause too.

548
00:33:55,231 --> 00:33:58,462
That is why I sent Trowbridge to ask Sir William

549
00:33:58,551 --> 00:34:00,507
to remind the King...

550
00:34:00,591 --> 00:34:02,547
What is the matter?

551
00:34:09,111 --> 00:34:12,183
Oh... Why, I'm sorry, yes.

552
00:34:13,911 --> 00:34:19,588
You must please excuse these little souvenirs
of Calvi and Tenerife.

553
00:34:19,671 --> 00:34:21,627
I had no idea.

554
00:34:21,711 --> 00:34:26,785
They told us of your victories,
but not of the price you had paid.

555
00:34:26,871 --> 00:34:29,180
Do not distress yourself, please.

556
00:34:29,271 --> 00:34:31,421
Tell me your news. Did Sir William see the King?

557
00:34:31,511 --> 00:34:34,708
- The King refused to see him.
- Refused to see the British Ambassador?

558
00:34:34,791 --> 00:34:37,225
I ought to have said
he was too terrified to see him.

559
00:34:37,311 --> 00:34:39,222
You cannot realise how Naples has changed.

560
00:34:39,311 --> 00:34:42,667
Have they gone out of their senses?
What do they think I am trying to do?

561
00:34:42,751 --> 00:34:46,221
Bonaparte's fleet is in Egypt.
For the first time I know where they are.

562
00:34:46,311 --> 00:34:49,462
If I can smash them up,
Europe has a chance to breathe again.

563
00:34:49,551 --> 00:34:51,507
And it's the first time he's been stopped.

564
00:34:51,591 --> 00:34:54,025
And yet they will not give me food or water
for my ships.

565
00:34:54,111 --> 00:34:56,466
When I saw that William was wasting his time,

566
00:34:56,551 --> 00:34:58,621
I took the liberty of seeing the Queen.

567
00:34:58,711 --> 00:35:02,067
I've never had such a time in all my life.
She's terrified of the French.

568
00:35:02,151 --> 00:35:04,745
- But I got it.
- What is that?

569
00:35:04,831 --> 00:35:07,504
A mandate, signed and sealed
by the Queen's own hand,

570
00:35:07,591 --> 00:35:12,028
for the full watering and victualling of the British
fleet in any port in the Kingdom of Naples.

571
00:35:12,111 --> 00:35:13,863
There.

572
00:35:22,871 --> 00:35:27,422
Look out, Bonaparte.
By gad, we shall lick you now.

573
00:35:36,671 --> 00:35:38,627
Tell the Queen I kiss her letter.

574
00:35:38,711 --> 00:35:43,102
Tell her I hope to kiss her hand
when we return from our victory.

575
00:35:44,191 --> 00:35:46,227
Won't you sit down? You must be tired.

576
00:35:50,911 --> 00:35:54,142
Do you remember the picnic we planned at
Capri on your ship?

577
00:35:54,231 --> 00:35:58,144
When I was going to dance in the moonlight
with my hair down five years ago.

578
00:35:58,231 --> 00:35:59,983
Or was it five centuries?

579
00:36:00,071 --> 00:36:02,187
When I rudely sailed away.

580
00:36:02,271 --> 00:36:06,708
And now you're going to rudely sail away again.
How's it been with you all these years?

581
00:36:06,791 --> 00:36:08,861
Alone, you know.

582
00:36:08,951 --> 00:36:12,023
You've done a great many things.
How is your wife?

583
00:36:12,111 --> 00:36:14,864
Oh, she's well enough, I believe.

584
00:36:14,951 --> 00:36:17,067
And when are you going to meet Bonaparte?

585
00:36:17,151 --> 00:36:18,982
- Soon, I hope.
- He's got haIf of Europe

586
00:36:19,071 --> 00:36:20,390
Now it's Egypt.

587
00:36:20,471 --> 00:36:21,950
Tomorrow it may be lndia.

588
00:36:22,031 --> 00:36:24,909
We are alone, but unafraid.

589
00:36:24,991 --> 00:36:26,470
SAlLOR: Haul away!

590
00:36:26,551 --> 00:36:28,064
You long to leave, don't you?

591
00:36:28,151 --> 00:36:30,107
Never lose an hour or waste a wind

592
00:36:30,191 --> 00:36:33,422
Goodbye, Sir Horatio.
It's a bit of a mouthful, isn't it?

593
00:36:33,511 --> 00:36:35,467
Yes. Goodbye, Lady Hamilton.

594
00:36:35,551 --> 00:36:38,349
You've helped us for the second time.

595
00:36:39,711 --> 00:36:43,624
EMMA:
He didn't lose an hour. He didn't waste a wind.

596
00:36:43,711 --> 00:36:47,147
He met his great opponent
and he defeated him on the Nile

597
00:36:48,511 --> 00:36:55,110
And when the battle was over
he didn't go back to his country or to his king

598
00:36:55,191 --> 00:36:57,147
or to his wife

599
00:36:57,231 --> 00:36:59,187
he came back

600
00:36:59,271 --> 00:37:00,829
to me

601
00:37:02,671 --> 00:37:04,627
(Band plays)
? A Life On The Ocean Wave

602
00:37:25,311 --> 00:37:28,303
? Fanfare

603
00:37:38,271 --> 00:37:40,739
- Stop. Fetch a doctor quickly.
(Band stops playing)

604
00:37:40,831 --> 00:37:43,789
Fetch a doctor quickly. Send everyone away.
A doctor quickly.

605
00:37:43,871 --> 00:37:46,146
(Murmuring)

606
00:37:52,071 --> 00:37:54,027
What's come over you, madam?

607
00:37:57,831 --> 00:37:59,981
A doctor? Who wants a doctor?

608
00:38:01,791 --> 00:38:04,703
But you staggered out there and nearly fell.

609
00:38:05,751 --> 00:38:07,707
I'm perfectly well.

610
00:38:13,471 --> 00:38:15,427
GUARD: Shoul...der!

611
00:38:21,951 --> 00:38:24,511
Your Majesty, I'm amazed.

612
00:38:24,591 --> 00:38:26,741
Cosa dice?

613
00:38:26,831 --> 00:38:29,106
l must speak to the King. Help me, Sir William.

614
00:38:31,071 --> 00:38:32,902
Lui vuole parlare con te.

615
00:38:32,991 --> 00:38:34,265
Va bene.

616
00:38:34,351 --> 00:38:36,865
Aspetta qui.

617
00:38:38,951 --> 00:38:41,226
Tell him I didn't come to Naples to be feted.

618
00:38:41,311 --> 00:38:44,462
In other times, I should be grateful,
but today I am appalled by it.

619
00:38:44,551 --> 00:38:47,941
I came here expecting to find an armed camp
and I find this tragic carnival.

620
00:38:48,031 --> 00:38:51,501
This Battle of the Nile that he's celebrating
may have destroyed their fleet,

621
00:38:51,591 --> 00:38:54,230
but his army's as strong as ever
and two days' from Naples.

622
00:38:54,311 --> 00:38:57,781
Yet the men of Naples dance in the streets
with paper caps and toy balloons.

623
00:38:57,871 --> 00:39:01,500
Maestà, Nelson dice che non è venuto
à Napoli per...

624
00:39:01,591 --> 00:39:03,502
Qu'est qu'il y a, ma chère?

625
00:39:04,551 --> 00:39:08,624
He says he has confidence in the English
and feels sure they will do what is necessary.

626
00:39:08,711 --> 00:39:12,909
Well, tell him we're not the guardian angels of
every country too lazy to look after itself.

627
00:39:12,991 --> 00:39:14,947
You've got to do something too!

628
00:39:15,031 --> 00:39:18,706
At the Nile, we cleared them off the seas,
but as long as they have armies on land,

629
00:39:18,791 --> 00:39:22,181
no country in Europe is free.
They want to get hold of the whole world.

630
00:39:22,391 --> 00:39:24,746
If you value your freedom, stir yourselves.

631
00:39:24,831 --> 00:39:27,061
Prepare and help drive them off the land!

632
00:39:27,151 --> 00:39:29,142
Ma perche l'Ammiraglio è cosi nervoso?

633
00:39:29,231 --> 00:39:32,029
I'm talking of Bonaparte, Your Majesty!
Bonaparte!

634
00:39:32,111 --> 00:39:37,504
Either advance toward him sword in hand
or else be kicked out of your kingdom.

635
00:39:37,591 --> 00:39:40,105
Lady Hamilton, may I speak to you?

636
00:39:47,831 --> 00:39:49,708
You called for a doctor just now.

637
00:39:49,791 --> 00:39:53,022
I'm so sorry. I didn't mean to upset you.
I thought you were ill.

638
00:39:53,111 --> 00:39:55,784
Well, for heaven's sake...

639
00:39:57,271 --> 00:39:59,227
..where is the doctor?

640
00:40:17,351 --> 00:40:19,911
This is the third time you've helped me.

641
00:40:27,911 --> 00:40:31,267
You've been here night and day. How long?

642
00:40:31,351 --> 00:40:33,307
EMMA: Nine days

643
00:40:35,231 --> 00:40:37,665
- What an enormous bed.
- It's my bed

644
00:40:39,071 --> 00:40:40,789
There's room for six people in it.

645
00:40:40,871 --> 00:40:43,180
There may be. I've never tried.

646
00:40:43,271 --> 00:40:44,829
Why am in your bed?

647
00:40:44,911 --> 00:40:47,061
They couldn't move you to the hospital

648
00:40:50,991 --> 00:40:55,587
Of all that ghastly crowd, you were
the only one who knew that I was ill.

649
00:40:55,671 --> 00:40:57,627
A nice cup of beef tea.

650
00:40:58,831 --> 00:41:01,948
- That'll put some go into him.
- Who's that?

651
00:41:02,031 --> 00:41:03,987
It's all right, milord. Just Emma's mother.

652
00:41:04,071 --> 00:41:06,027
Emma's mother...

653
00:41:07,111 --> 00:41:09,579
..do you think I could call her Emma too?

654
00:41:09,671 --> 00:41:12,947
Why ask me?
You've been calling her Emma all this time.

655
00:41:13,031 --> 00:41:14,987
Now, don't say anymore.

656
00:41:16,391 --> 00:41:18,347
Here you are.

657
00:41:19,391 --> 00:41:20,744
There.

658
00:41:20,831 --> 00:41:24,460
Now I'll tell you all the news
and all the gossip too, if you're interested.

659
00:41:24,551 --> 00:41:28,783
First item, the King of England is pleased
to elevate Sir Horatio Nelson to the peerage.

660
00:41:28,871 --> 00:41:30,827
You are now Lord Nelson.

661
00:41:30,911 --> 00:41:35,063
Second item, the King of Naples has given you
the dukedom of Bronte.

662
00:41:35,151 --> 00:41:37,301
You are now a duke and a baron.

663
00:41:37,391 --> 00:41:41,430
Third item, the whole of Europe sings
your praises, the victor of the Nile.

664
00:41:41,511 --> 00:41:44,423
It wouldn't have been possible without you.

665
00:41:44,511 --> 00:41:47,821
I'm going to tell them.
I'm going to let the whole world know.

666
00:41:47,911 --> 00:41:50,141
I told you not to talk. You've got to rest.

667
00:41:50,231 --> 00:41:54,270
In a week, you can get up. Then for another
week, you can have nothing but goat's milk.

668
00:41:54,351 --> 00:41:58,629
Disgusting.
I shall be able to get up in a day or two..

669
00:41:58,711 --> 00:42:01,908
You can get up
when you are told you can get up.

670
00:42:01,991 --> 00:42:05,267
Yes, ma'am. Goat's milk for a week and
I get up when I'm told.

671
00:42:05,351 --> 00:42:07,307
(Laughs) That's better.

672
00:42:07,391 --> 00:42:09,347
We need you now, Lord Nelson.

673
00:42:09,431 --> 00:42:11,661
In these times the whole world needs you.

674
00:42:11,751 --> 00:42:13,707
And I need you more than anyone else.

675
00:42:13,791 --> 00:42:17,227
As soon as you are well, the King has
commanded a gala performance of the opera

676
00:42:17,311 --> 00:42:19,586
and I want to wear my new dress from London.

677
00:42:20,471 --> 00:42:21,824
Gala performance?

678
00:42:21,911 --> 00:42:24,550
Opera?
When they ought to be mobilising armies.

679
00:42:24,631 --> 00:42:27,065
They're doomed and don't want to realise it.

680
00:42:27,151 --> 00:42:29,107
You mustn't excite yourself.

681
00:42:32,991 --> 00:42:37,189
Would you do me a kindness
and write a letter for me, Emma?

682
00:42:37,271 --> 00:42:38,750
Of course.

683
00:42:40,591 --> 00:42:42,547
To whom?

684
00:42:42,631 --> 00:42:44,542
Lady Nelson.

685
00:42:46,111 --> 00:42:50,024
Burnham Thorpe Norfolk England

686
00:42:53,551 --> 00:42:55,587
I wonder what she looks like now.

687
00:42:55,671 --> 00:42:57,627
I haven't seen her for seven years

688
00:42:57,711 --> 00:43:00,350
I wonder why we sailors ever marry

689
00:43:00,431 --> 00:43:02,262
Do you want that to go in?

690
00:43:02,351 --> 00:43:05,229
Good heavens, no. (Laughs)

691
00:43:06,951 --> 00:43:08,907
My dear wife

692
00:43:08,991 --> 00:43:10,629
My dear wife...

693
00:43:10,711 --> 00:43:13,783
My heartiest greetings from Naples
to you and Father.

694
00:43:16,671 --> 00:43:18,627
I'm in the house of the Hamiltons

695
00:43:18,711 --> 00:43:25,787
and it has taken all their care
and kindness to pull me through.

696
00:43:25,871 --> 00:43:32,106
I hope some day to have the pleasure
of introducing you to Lady Hamilton

697
00:43:33,711 --> 00:43:38,626
Lady Hamilton is one of the very best women
in the world...

698
00:43:40,831 --> 00:43:43,186
and an honour to her sex

699
00:43:53,991 --> 00:43:58,587
? La ci darem la mano

700
00:43:58,671 --> 00:44:02,346
? La mi dirai di si

701
00:44:03,631 --> 00:44:07,909
? Vedi, non è lontano

702
00:44:07,991 --> 00:44:12,621
? Partiam, ben mio, da qui

703
00:44:12,711 --> 00:44:15,020
? Vorrei e mon ver-rai

704
00:44:15,111 --> 00:44:17,067
(King hums)

705
00:44:17,151 --> 00:44:18,869
Ferdinando!

706
00:44:18,951 --> 00:44:23,263
? Mi tremaun pocoil cor

707
00:44:23,351 --> 00:44:27,629
? Felice e ver sarei

708
00:44:27,711 --> 00:44:32,705
? Ma puo burlarmiancor

709
00:44:35,071 --> 00:44:39,587
? Neopolitan folk song

710
00:44:55,151 --> 00:44:58,268
Do you know what they're having
at the palace now?

711
00:44:58,351 --> 00:45:00,945
Mushrooms from Switzerland,
pheasants from England,

712
00:45:01,031 --> 00:45:02,703
wine from Spain.

713
00:45:02,791 --> 00:45:05,225
120 years old and £5 a bottle.

714
00:45:05,311 --> 00:45:07,666
And here sits the hero of the evening
missing it all.

715
00:45:09,831 --> 00:45:11,469
Are you missing it all?

716
00:45:11,551 --> 00:45:14,827
Of course not. The real and exclusive party
of the evening is here.

717
00:45:14,911 --> 00:45:17,709
Besides, I know exactly
what's happening at the palace.

718
00:45:17,791 --> 00:45:19,747
The Queen...

719
00:45:19,831 --> 00:45:22,220
Ferdinando! Taci! Taci! Ferdinando!

720
00:45:22,311 --> 00:45:25,826
And the King, the poor little King
with 15 children and the Kingdom of Naples

721
00:45:25,911 --> 00:45:28,061
and never an answer to give to his queen.

722
00:45:28,151 --> 00:45:30,107
And here sits the British Ambassador.

723
00:45:30,191 --> 00:45:33,103
Bored and dreaming only
of his last statue from Pompeii.

724
00:45:33,191 --> 00:45:36,501
And throughout the evening
there sits Lord Nelson,

725
00:45:36,591 --> 00:45:39,469
exhibiting his various moods one by one.

726
00:45:39,551 --> 00:45:41,985
Lord Nelson in a bad mood.

727
00:45:42,071 --> 00:45:44,027
Lord Nelson in a good mood.

728
00:45:44,111 --> 00:45:45,988
Lord Nelson in an exuberant mood.

729
00:45:47,231 --> 00:45:50,189
(He laughs) Am I really such a dull fellow?

730
00:45:50,271 --> 00:45:52,501
Only when you ask questions like that.

731
00:45:52,591 --> 00:45:55,628
And now it's my turn to give you
a little presentation.

732
00:45:55,711 --> 00:45:57,383
What mood is this?

733
00:45:57,471 --> 00:45:59,507
One guess.

734
00:46:03,071 --> 00:46:08,384
Nelson allowing himself
to be just a little bit happy?

735
00:46:11,271 --> 00:46:13,102
Nelson in love.

736
00:46:22,471 --> 00:46:25,031
(Raucous laughter)

737
00:46:27,991 --> 00:46:29,709
(Outburst of laughter)

738
00:46:35,431 --> 00:46:37,899
Of all the inns in Naples, you choose this one.

739
00:46:37,991 --> 00:46:42,542
Probably the last place in Naples
where they expected to find me.

740
00:46:42,631 --> 00:46:44,428
Were you at the opera tonight, my dear?

741
00:46:44,511 --> 00:46:46,467
No? You should have been.

742
00:46:46,551 --> 00:46:48,781
There was quite a profusion of barmaids.

743
00:46:48,871 --> 00:46:52,102
Some even found their way to the royal box

744
00:46:52,191 --> 00:46:53,783
(Laughter)

745
00:46:53,871 --> 00:46:55,384
He's drunk.

746
00:46:55,471 --> 00:46:59,066
l see you're not married, my dear. What a pity.

747
00:46:59,151 --> 00:47:02,826
Married women are bestowing their favours
so cheaply these days

748
00:47:02,911 --> 00:47:05,744
He's never behaved like this before.

749
00:47:05,831 --> 00:47:09,506
Friends, I give you the real hero of the hour.

750
00:47:09,591 --> 00:47:11,229
Sir William Hamilton.

751
00:47:11,311 --> 00:47:13,267
(Laughter)

752
00:47:18,111 --> 00:47:20,067
That's an excellent toast, Josiah.

753
00:47:21,351 --> 00:47:23,228
May I drink it with you?

754
00:47:27,471 --> 00:47:29,621
Thank you.

755
00:47:29,711 --> 00:47:31,190
Sir William Hamilton.

756
00:47:35,111 --> 00:47:37,545
Lady Hamilton and I are leaving. Fetch a cab.

757
00:47:39,391 --> 00:47:41,700
Don't let us disturb you, lads. You're off duty.

758
00:47:46,551 --> 00:47:48,064
Enjoy yourselves.

759
00:47:56,511 --> 00:47:58,467
Forgive them, my dear.

760
00:47:58,551 --> 00:48:00,985
They are very... very young.

761
00:48:02,031 --> 00:48:03,942
I have forgiven them.

762
00:48:04,991 --> 00:48:06,902
That's the way people look at these things.

763
00:48:06,991 --> 00:48:10,347
They do not believe in a friendship
between a man and a woman.

764
00:48:13,271 --> 00:48:15,182
Do you?

765
00:48:52,311 --> 00:48:54,267
All right, later. Later.

766
00:48:58,991 --> 00:49:01,710
It was magnificent! Stupendous!

767
00:49:01,791 --> 00:49:03,827
Wasn't I wonderful, William?

768
00:49:03,911 --> 00:49:05,503
Wasn't it a success?

769
00:49:05,591 --> 00:49:08,822
A triumph.
The greatest ball ever seen in Naples.

770
00:49:08,911 --> 00:49:10,867
You were stupendous.

771
00:49:10,951 --> 00:49:14,261
You entertained 200 people as easily
as you enchant a solitary husband.

772
00:49:14,351 --> 00:49:20,028
The King said to me, ''Milady, la sua bellezza mi
fa dimenticare tutte le pensieri della realta.''

773
00:49:20,111 --> 00:49:23,990
And Hardy, good old Hardy said,
''Well, I'll be blowed, Your Ladyship.

774
00:49:24,071 --> 00:49:27,541
What I mean to say is,
well, you know what I mean.''

775
00:49:27,631 --> 00:49:30,350
And... Oh, goodness! I'm so tired!

776
00:49:30,431 --> 00:49:31,944
What did he say?

777
00:49:32,031 --> 00:49:33,384
He who?

778
00:49:33,471 --> 00:49:34,904
He.

779
00:49:35,951 --> 00:49:39,148
Oh, he didn't say anything.
He never says much, you know.

780
00:49:39,231 --> 00:49:42,906
People were saying that he should have sat
on your right during dinner,

781
00:49:42,991 --> 00:49:44,185
not on your left

782
00:49:44,271 --> 00:49:48,389
What? And give the Queen the side
with the eye on it? Not likely.

783
00:49:48,471 --> 00:49:49,745
He seemed very happy.

784
00:49:49,831 --> 00:49:53,141
Yes, I really think he's better now.

785
00:49:53,231 --> 00:49:55,506
Tonight, he seemed to forget everything.

786
00:49:55,591 --> 00:49:57,741
Ships, the war, Napoleon, everything.

787
00:49:57,831 --> 00:50:01,619
Could any man think of worldly cares
in the spell of Emma's magic?

788
00:50:01,711 --> 00:50:04,350
He deserved his happiness this evening

789
00:50:04,431 --> 00:50:08,219
After such happiness how sad to find oneself
the next morning at sea again.

790
00:50:08,311 --> 00:50:10,267
And at war

791
00:50:11,951 --> 00:50:14,863
What do you mean?
We're going to Pompeii tomorrow.

792
00:50:14,951 --> 00:50:16,703
Lord Nelson will be on his way to Malta.

793
00:50:16,791 --> 00:50:19,225
I think there must be some mistake, William.

794
00:50:19,311 --> 00:50:22,781
Lord Nelson left ten minutes ago and said
he would be with us at 12 tomorrow.

795
00:50:22,871 --> 00:50:25,749
The dispatch arrived while dessert
was being served.

796
00:50:25,831 --> 00:50:27,901
I had it sent straight aboard his ship

797
00:50:27,991 --> 00:50:30,949
He's probably reading it at this very moment

798
00:50:32,031 --> 00:50:34,261
Why didn't you tell me this before, William?

799
00:50:34,351 --> 00:50:37,946
But my dear I wouldn't have spoilt
your evening for anything in the world

800
00:50:38,031 --> 00:50:40,545
You mean,
you wouldn't have spoiled yours for anything.

801
00:50:40,631 --> 00:50:44,101
You tried to prevent me
from saying goodbye to him

802
00:50:46,111 --> 00:50:47,510
You know Emma

803
00:50:47,591 --> 00:50:50,742
there are three kinds of deceived husbands
in the world.

804
00:50:50,831 --> 00:50:53,345
First there are those
who were born to be deceived.

805
00:50:53,431 --> 00:50:55,387
Second, who do not know.

806
00:50:55,471 --> 00:50:57,746
And third, who do not care.

807
00:50:57,831 --> 00:51:01,870
I've been wondering for some time now,
which of the three I should be myself.

808
00:51:01,951 --> 00:51:04,419
Have you forgotten the fourth kind, William?

809
00:51:04,511 --> 00:51:08,629
The kind that is hard and empty
and gives nothing.

810
00:51:09,711 --> 00:51:12,942
You married me because you wanted
a new ornament for your house.

811
00:51:13,031 --> 00:51:16,501
Like that painting or that statue or that vase.

812
00:51:17,551 --> 00:51:20,782
As far as you're concerned,
I'm just as ornamental.

813
00:51:20,871 --> 00:51:22,589
And just as dead.

814
00:51:22,671 --> 00:51:25,902
But, my dear,
how can you call my statues dead?

815
00:51:25,991 --> 00:51:30,667
When I'm alone and rather tired, think what
it means for me to have my statues with me.

816
00:51:30,751 --> 00:51:33,219
To know that they'll always be lovely,

817
00:51:33,311 --> 00:51:37,099
will never grow old,
and never walk out with sailors.

818
00:51:42,111 --> 00:51:44,420
What a pity you're not going to see him again.

819
00:51:44,511 --> 00:51:47,947
It would have been a farewell scene
of lasting beauty.

820
00:51:48,031 --> 00:51:49,987
I shall sleep beautifully tonight.

821
00:51:50,071 --> 00:51:52,027
Good night, my dear.

822
00:52:08,591 --> 00:52:12,630
My darling...come back.

823
00:52:14,031 --> 00:52:15,987
Come back.

824
00:52:18,271 --> 00:52:22,822
Emily, he's waiting for you...out on the balcony.

825
00:53:02,911 --> 00:53:04,867
(Bell rings)

826
00:53:04,951 --> 00:53:06,907
(Foghorn)

827
00:53:10,071 --> 00:53:13,666
You shouldn't have come.
People will see you. They'll talk.

828
00:53:13,751 --> 00:53:16,140
Oh, let them talk. I don't care. Do you?

829
00:53:16,231 --> 00:53:18,222
Are you sorry?

830
00:53:18,311 --> 00:53:21,542
I'm only sorry for all the wasted years
I've been without you.

831
00:53:21,631 --> 00:53:23,861
For all the years I shall have to be without you.

832
00:53:23,951 --> 00:53:25,623
You'll come back, won't you?

833
00:53:26,671 --> 00:53:28,627
I wonder if I shall.

834
00:53:28,711 --> 00:53:30,667
I feel I should not.

835
00:53:30,751 --> 00:53:32,707
You are married and I am married.

836
00:53:33,991 --> 00:53:37,904
In the magic and music and the ballroom,
these things become rather blurred.

837
00:53:37,991 --> 00:53:40,346
But they stand out very clearly in the dawn.

838
00:53:41,791 --> 00:53:43,702
Your life is here.

839
00:53:43,791 --> 00:53:47,864
My life is...there.

840
00:53:49,191 --> 00:53:52,661
We must obey the creeds and codes
that we've sworn our lives to.

841
00:53:53,751 --> 00:53:55,423
kn ow t h at must n ot co m e back

842
00:53:56,951 --> 00:53:59,909
And I know that nothing in this world
can keep me away.

843
00:54:06,911 --> 00:54:08,867
FlRST MATE: Up oars!

844
00:54:25,671 --> 00:54:27,070
Down!

845
00:54:27,151 --> 00:54:30,223
Pull, oarsmen!

846
00:54:38,311 --> 00:54:40,063
Together!

847
00:54:53,511 --> 00:54:55,467
(Wind roars)

848
00:55:04,391 --> 00:55:08,669
If I understand you correctly, sir,
our first objective is to recover Malta.

849
00:55:08,751 --> 00:55:12,630
In that case, I suggest we send
the Culloden, the Lion and the Goliath,

850
00:55:12,711 --> 00:55:15,748
under Ball, to blockade the island
and then take possession of it.

851
00:55:44,671 --> 00:55:46,423
Aiuto!

852
00:55:54,191 --> 00:55:55,590
BO'SUN: Excuse me, sir.

853
00:55:55,671 --> 00:55:56,786
What is it?

854
00:55:56,871 --> 00:56:00,864
We've just picked up a fishing boat
with refugees from Naples

855
00:56:00,951 --> 00:56:02,748
Refugees from Naples?

856
00:56:02,831 --> 00:56:04,981
Yes, sir. They say revolution has broken out.

857
00:56:05,071 --> 00:56:09,622
The Government got away, but the King
and Queen are locked up in the palace.

858
00:56:09,711 --> 00:56:11,702
I don't understand everything he says sir

859
00:56:11,791 --> 00:56:15,830
but there must be plenty of shooting looting
and murdering in the town

860
00:56:20,391 --> 00:56:24,225
That's what you've always said, sir.
Just wait until we've gone. Serves them right.

861
00:56:24,311 --> 00:56:26,825
If they can't help themselves nobody else can

862
00:56:26,911 --> 00:56:29,709
This is Lord Keith's orders
We've got to meet the Alexander

863
00:56:29,791 --> 00:56:32,624
the Foudroyant and the Minotaur
at the point of intersection

864
00:56:37,631 --> 00:56:40,464
Blackwood, go back to your ship.

865
00:56:41,511 --> 00:56:44,947
Arrange with Ball to blockade Malta.

866
00:56:45,031 --> 00:56:47,625
The rest of the fleet sails to Messina

867
00:56:47,711 --> 00:56:50,430
Well, what course are you taking, sir?

868
00:56:52,191 --> 00:56:54,068
Back to Naples.

869
00:56:57,431 --> 00:56:59,262
What are you waiting for, Trowbridge?

870
00:56:59,351 --> 00:57:01,387
But, sir, Lord Keith's orders...

871
00:57:01,471 --> 00:57:04,827
Lord Keith's orders are addressed to me!
Mine are addressed to you.

872
00:57:04,911 --> 00:57:07,425
- Yes, sir.
- Return to your ships at once

873
00:57:13,911 --> 00:57:15,867
HARDY: May I speak sir?

874
00:57:18,351 --> 00:57:19,670
Yes.

875
00:57:19,751 --> 00:57:22,219
I'm under your order, sir. I'll do as I'm told.

876
00:57:22,311 --> 00:57:25,940
I'll sail this ship anywhere
where there's water under her keel.

877
00:57:26,031 --> 00:57:28,625
But I implore you,
call Blackwood and Trowbridge back,

878
00:57:28,711 --> 00:57:30,542
and send the fleet where it's ordered to

879
00:57:30,631 --> 00:57:34,101
And leave our allies the King and Queen
of Naples at the mercy of that rabble?

880
00:57:34,191 --> 00:57:36,147
You know what that mob will do to them.

881
00:57:36,231 --> 00:57:38,984
Do you want them to build that bestial guillotine
in Naples?

882
00:57:39,071 --> 00:57:42,268
But in London they will say
it wasn't the Royal Family you went back for.

883
00:57:42,351 --> 00:57:44,546
- Be careful what you say!
- I will say it!

884
00:57:44,631 --> 00:57:46,349
They will say it was for Lady Hamilton.

885
00:57:46,431 --> 00:57:48,991
Let them say it. Let them say what they wish!

886
00:57:49,071 --> 00:57:53,189
l will not see those I love
and owe loyalty to left alone.

887
00:57:56,911 --> 00:57:58,867
Back to Naples

888
00:57:58,951 --> 00:58:00,907
I understand, sir.

889
00:58:16,431 --> 00:58:20,424
In the face of such open disobedience,
I must ask your Lordships for a clear decision.

890
00:58:20,511 --> 00:58:22,229
Where is Nelson now?

891
00:58:22,311 --> 00:58:26,509
At Palermo, where he took the whole party
after he got them away from Naples.

892
00:58:27,751 --> 00:58:31,664
As much as I dislike discussing personalities
and private matters,

893
00:58:31,751 --> 00:58:35,744
I must say he does not behave in a manner
befitting a British Admiral.

894
00:58:35,831 --> 00:58:38,664
Hear, hear.
I quite agree with what you're saying.

895
00:58:39,031 --> 00:58:40,464
Gentlemen.

896
00:58:40,551 --> 00:58:41,620
Gentlemen.

897
00:58:41,711 --> 00:58:44,748
Lord Nelson has some excuse
for his disobedience.

898
00:58:44,831 --> 00:58:47,186
How can there be an excuse for disobedience?

899
00:58:47,271 --> 00:58:52,345
He did save the royal family of an allied nation
from certain death at the hands of the mob.

900
00:58:52,431 --> 00:58:55,070
He also saved the British Ambassador
and his wife.

901
00:58:55,151 --> 00:58:58,188
- What's the point of saving the husband?
- (Laughter)

902
00:58:59,911 --> 00:59:01,867
Yes, you think it very funny.

903
00:59:01,951 --> 00:59:04,784
The whole of England thinks it's funny.
The whole of Europe.

904
00:59:04,871 --> 00:59:07,988
- But it's high time that...
- Steady, Keith. Steady.

905
00:59:08,071 --> 00:59:11,950
No-one questions the seriousness of this matter.

906
00:59:12,031 --> 00:59:14,545
Lord Nelson is a very gallant sailor.

907
00:59:14,631 --> 00:59:17,543
But not even the greatest hero is strong enough

908
00:59:17,631 --> 00:59:20,828
to defeat the prejudices
and conventions of society.

909
00:59:20,911 --> 00:59:23,744
We must be tolerant of poor Nelson.

910
00:59:23,831 --> 00:59:26,299
lt'd be best to bring him home at once.

911
00:59:26,391 --> 00:59:31,465
Let him say farewell
to this charming little romance of his.

912
00:59:31,551 --> 00:59:35,066
Let him forget the beautiful Emma.

913
00:59:45,111 --> 00:59:48,069
- Oh, that's appalling.
- It's wonderful, magnificent.

914
00:59:48,151 --> 00:59:51,268
- This time we have them at our mercy.
- That's the worst hand we've had.

915
00:59:51,351 --> 00:59:53,546
I know, but we will bluff them. Smile, just smile.

916
00:59:53,631 --> 00:59:55,462
Fortunately, they don't understand us.

917
00:59:55,551 --> 00:59:57,985
- Possiamo cominciare, Signora?
- Qual è la posta?

918
00:59:58,071 --> 00:59:59,390
- Il doppio.
- Il doppio.

919
00:59:59,471 --> 01:00:02,383
- But we haven't a chance.
- We shall in a minute. Smile.

920
01:00:02,471 --> 01:00:05,031
- The seven of diamonds.
- The ace of diamonds.

921
01:00:05,111 --> 01:00:07,067
There, you see.

922
01:00:07,151 --> 01:00:09,107
The queen of clubs.

923
01:00:09,191 --> 01:00:12,422
- But that's mad...
- Treble the stakes! Triplichiamo la posta.

924
01:00:12,511 --> 01:00:15,025
- But, darling...
- The king of spades.

925
01:00:16,311 --> 01:00:18,267
The seven of diamonds.

926
01:00:18,351 --> 01:00:20,228
And the ace of hearts.

927
01:00:20,311 --> 01:00:22,267
E bene, signori, a mio parere.

928
01:00:22,351 --> 01:00:25,627
- Molta fortunata, signora.
- Bravissimo, signora.

929
01:00:25,711 --> 01:00:29,021
By gad, you're impudent. What would
you have done if the bluff had failed?

930
01:00:29,111 --> 01:00:32,069
I would have fainted and upset the table.
Now let us go.

931
01:00:32,151 --> 01:00:34,984
We can't go. We must give them a chance
to retrieve their losses.

932
01:00:35,071 --> 01:00:37,301
Would they give you a chance? No, come along.

933
01:00:37,391 --> 01:00:42,146
I'll order the carriage and we'll drive home
by the sea. The air in here is unbearable.

934
01:00:42,231 --> 01:00:44,301
Arrividerci, signori. Bon soir, monsieur.

935
01:00:44,391 --> 01:00:45,983
In a minute.

936
01:00:52,751 --> 01:00:55,982
Emma, there's a matter of some importance
that I must speak to you about.

937
01:00:56,071 --> 01:00:58,027
Yes, William.

938
01:00:58,111 --> 01:01:00,864
Ten days ago,
a dispatch came from the Admiralty,

939
01:01:00,951 --> 01:01:04,387
instructing Nelson in very definite terms
to report in London at once.

940
01:01:04,471 --> 01:01:06,427
What is all this to do with me?

941
01:01:06,511 --> 01:01:09,901
Well, if Nelson ignores this final order,
there can be only one result.

942
01:01:09,991 --> 01:01:12,744
Dismissal from the Navy
and the end of his career.

943
01:01:12,831 --> 01:01:16,744
ls it worth it, Emma?
His future is in your hands, you know that.

944
01:01:19,431 --> 01:01:23,709
Very well. If we must go back, we must go back.

945
01:01:23,791 --> 01:01:27,181
I'll tell him tonight.
When do you wish us to leave?

946
01:01:27,271 --> 01:01:29,227
We are not going to leave, Emma.

947
01:01:29,311 --> 01:01:33,748
My instructions from the Admiralty say
that Nelson is to return alone.

948
01:01:33,831 --> 01:01:35,787
Oh, I understand.

949
01:01:35,871 --> 01:01:38,943
The Admiralty is anxious to save him from me.

950
01:01:39,031 --> 01:01:41,181
And what am I expected to do?

951
01:01:41,271 --> 01:01:46,664
It will be convenient, my dear. The Turkish
envoy has invited you to winter in Cairo.

952
01:01:46,751 --> 01:01:50,790
Tell Nelson that you love Egypt
and that you have accepted the invitation.

953
01:01:50,871 --> 01:01:53,908
You can be wonderfully convincing
when you try Emma

954
01:01:53,991 --> 01:01:59,349
The moment you leave for Egypt he will have
no alternative but to obey orders and return

955
01:01:59,431 --> 01:02:03,902
I know I'm asking you to do a very difficult
and painful duty.

956
01:02:06,471 --> 01:02:08,029
Thank you, William.

957
01:02:08,111 --> 01:02:10,181
Well, we both have our duty, haven't we?

958
01:02:11,271 --> 01:02:13,227
Good luck with yours, my dear.

959
01:02:39,431 --> 01:02:42,025
Well, I lost everything. I feel better for it.

960
01:02:44,671 --> 01:02:46,309
What is the matter, my dear?

961
01:02:46,391 --> 01:02:48,347
William has just been talking to me.

962
01:02:48,431 --> 01:02:51,787
Telling me of the repeated dispatches
from the Admiralty.

963
01:02:51,871 --> 01:02:54,943
He also wanted me to put on
a little performance for you.

964
01:02:55,031 --> 01:03:00,310
Act One. Emma Hamilton expresses a sudden
desire to see the Sphinx and the pyramids.

965
01:03:00,391 --> 01:03:04,145
Act Two. Lord Nelson pleads,
Emma Hamilton remains adamant.

966
01:03:04,231 --> 01:03:07,268
Act Three. Emma Hamilton departs for Egypt.

967
01:03:07,351 --> 01:03:11,469
And Lord Nelson returns to London
a sadder and wiser man.

968
01:03:11,551 --> 01:03:16,420
Poor William, he was so serious about it all. I'm
convinced he was only thinking of your career.

969
01:03:16,511 --> 01:03:20,470
He'd been puzzling through all sorts of stories.
What hadn't occurred to him was the truth.

970
01:03:20,551 --> 01:03:25,306
How silly. How utterly silly.
To think that we should need lies, you and l.

971
01:03:37,831 --> 01:03:39,549
Oh, my darling.

972
01:03:39,631 --> 01:03:41,587
What is the truth?

973
01:03:41,671 --> 01:03:44,743
Should I have put on that comedy for you?

974
01:03:46,071 --> 01:03:48,710
- It might have helped perhaps.
- Oh, no.

975
01:03:48,791 --> 01:03:51,259
I cannot put it off any longer.

976
01:03:52,471 --> 01:03:53,950
I must go back this time.

977
01:03:55,031 --> 01:03:58,262
They want me to go alone.

978
01:04:01,471 --> 01:04:03,427
Oh, of course, you must go.

979
01:04:04,391 --> 01:04:06,347
And, of course, I must go to Egypt.

980
01:04:06,431 --> 01:04:08,865
I don't want to be a burden to you, my darling.

981
01:04:09,991 --> 01:04:12,266
My darling.

982
01:04:12,351 --> 01:04:18,062
And, of course, I will enjoy seeing the pyramids
and the Sphinx and the Nile.

983
01:04:18,151 --> 01:04:19,903
Your Nile.

984
01:04:21,471 --> 01:04:23,462
Oh, my darling.

985
01:04:24,551 --> 01:04:27,304
Why do we always meet just to say goodbye?

986
01:04:31,591 --> 01:04:37,985
? At home I left a lovely maiden

987
01:04:38,071 --> 01:04:46,024
? With rosy cheeks and eyes of ocean blue

988
01:04:46,111 --> 01:04:54,109
? And though my heart is sad and heavy laden

989
01:04:55,071 --> 01:05:04,423
? To leave a lass I love so fond and true

990
01:05:04,511 --> 01:05:06,467
(Bell rings)

991
01:05:08,031 --> 01:05:09,987
What are those bells?

992
01:05:11,271 --> 01:05:13,341
Have you forgotten what night this is?

993
01:05:14,311 --> 01:05:16,267
The last of 1799.

994
01:05:17,751 --> 01:05:20,504
Eight bells for the old year
and eight for the new.

995
01:05:22,311 --> 01:05:24,267
Happy New Year, darling.

996
01:05:24,351 --> 01:05:26,660
apby New Yea r

997
01:05:26,751 --> 01:05:28,707
The dawn of a new century.

998
01:05:28,791 --> 01:05:30,747
1 800.

999
01:05:30,831 --> 01:05:33,265
How strange it sounds.

1000
01:05:34,311 --> 01:05:36,267
What a century it's been.

1001
01:05:38,311 --> 01:05:42,463
Marlborough rode to war
and Washington crossed the Delaware.

1002
01:05:43,791 --> 01:05:46,385
Louis XVl and Marie Antoinette.

1003
01:05:47,431 --> 01:05:49,581
The last of the Stuarts.

1004
01:05:49,671 --> 01:05:51,627
Peter The Great.

1005
01:05:51,711 --> 01:05:53,667
Voltaire.

1006
01:05:53,751 --> 01:05:55,707
Clive Of lndia.

1007
01:05:55,791 --> 01:05:57,543
Bonaparte.

1008
01:05:58,911 --> 01:06:00,583
Nelson.

1009
01:06:14,271 --> 01:06:18,230
Now I've kissed you through two centuries.

1010
01:06:19,391 --> 01:06:21,347
1 800.

1011
01:06:21,431 --> 01:06:24,423
The beginning of a new life for me.

1012
01:06:24,511 --> 01:06:26,388
A life without you.

1013
01:06:27,791 --> 01:06:30,259
How beautiful was the old century.

1014
01:06:31,431 --> 01:06:33,387
When I was with you.

1015
01:06:41,311 --> 01:06:44,621
Emma, say that you could never leave me.

1016
01:06:44,711 --> 01:06:46,667
I can never leave you.

1017
01:06:46,751 --> 01:06:48,901
Say that you hate the blasted pyramids.

1018
01:06:48,991 --> 01:06:50,424
I hate the pyramids.

1019
01:06:50,511 --> 01:06:52,388
That you never want to see the Sphinx.

1020
01:06:52,471 --> 01:06:54,268
I never want to see the Sphinx.

1021
01:06:54,351 --> 01:06:56,307
We'll go back to London together.

1022
01:06:56,391 --> 01:06:59,349
I would have died if you'd left me here.

1023
01:07:12,591 --> 01:07:14,547
I am Lady Nelson.

1024
01:07:15,911 --> 01:07:18,061
Everything has been prepared
for Your Ladyship.

1025
01:07:18,151 --> 01:07:20,346
Your rooms have been reserved
by the Admiralty.

1026
01:07:20,431 --> 01:07:22,467
Thank you. Kindly show me to my rooms.

1027
01:07:22,551 --> 01:07:26,226
You will find our bed linen in the green trunk.
We prefer our own sheets.

1028
01:07:26,311 --> 01:07:29,587
- Very good, Your Ladyship.
- Breakfast precisely at 6:45.

1029
01:07:29,671 --> 01:07:33,949
India tea with lemon, one four-minute egg,
two slices of thinly buttered toast.

1030
01:07:34,031 --> 01:07:36,181
I shall instruct the head waiter, Your Ladyship.

1031
01:07:36,271 --> 01:07:39,343
I dislike waiters in the rooms.
Would you arrange for a chambermaid?

1032
01:07:39,431 --> 01:07:41,387
As you wish...

1033
01:07:42,551 --> 01:07:47,341
Here, here. Go and drink a health
to Lord Nelson my son.

1034
01:07:47,431 --> 01:07:49,467
Thank you, sir. I will and be proud to.

1035
01:07:49,551 --> 01:07:54,306
I am deeply honoured to have you with us
on this great occasion, sir.

1036
01:07:54,391 --> 01:07:57,383
You are the guest of the British Admiralty,
Mr Nelson.

1037
01:07:57,471 --> 01:08:00,781
Good, then charge up a glass of port
to the British Admiralty.

1038
01:08:00,871 --> 01:08:03,669
And let's have it right away.
Anything for you, my dear?

1039
01:08:03,751 --> 01:08:08,586
No, thank you. One small glass of light port
for Mr Nelson and a warming pan for his bed.

1040
01:08:08,671 --> 01:08:10,627
Very good, Your Ladyship.

1041
01:08:10,711 --> 01:08:13,908
Wonderful! Wonderful! Lap of luxury.

1042
01:08:13,991 --> 01:08:16,869
No morning service and no chickens to feed.

1043
01:08:16,951 --> 01:08:19,419
Let's have breakfast in bed with two eggs, eh?

1044
01:08:19,511 --> 01:08:21,308
I've arranged everything, Father.

1045
01:08:21,391 --> 01:08:24,030
It's unwise to break good habits even in London.

1046
01:08:24,111 --> 01:08:26,864
You must remember Dr Ponsonby's words
of advice.

1047
01:08:26,951 --> 01:08:28,907
Dr Ponsonby's advice.

1048
01:08:28,991 --> 01:08:32,142
Did Dr Ponsonby's son ever sink
the French fleet?

1049
01:08:32,231 --> 01:08:34,984
- We're going to enjoy ourselves.
(Knock on door)

1050
01:08:35,071 --> 01:08:39,189
Your Ladyship, Lord Spencer is here
and wishes to be received.

1051
01:08:39,271 --> 01:08:41,227
Very well.

1052
01:08:52,671 --> 01:08:54,627
Good morning, Lady Nelson.

1053
01:08:54,711 --> 01:08:57,748
The Admiralty appreciates
your prompt response to its request.

1054
01:08:57,831 --> 01:09:00,391
I hope your accommodation is comfortable.

1055
01:09:00,471 --> 01:09:02,143
Quite, Lord Spencer, thank you.

1056
01:09:02,231 --> 01:09:04,187
- Pray, be seated.
- Thank you.

1057
01:09:04,271 --> 01:09:07,104
I assume that the Admiralty desires
my presence

1058
01:09:07,191 --> 01:09:10,900
to discuss the arrangements for my husband's
reception. When does he arrive?

1059
01:09:10,991 --> 01:09:13,551
He's already arrived, Lady Nelson.

1060
01:09:14,791 --> 01:09:15,940
What?

1061
01:09:16,031 --> 01:09:20,183
It was Lord Nelson's special wish
that his arrival should not be made public.

1062
01:09:20,271 --> 01:09:23,229
Did he include his wife in the term ''public''?

1063
01:09:23,311 --> 01:09:26,781
I don't recall the exact phraseology of the letter.

1064
01:09:26,871 --> 01:09:30,659
However, the Admiralty thought it advisable to
accede to his request.

1065
01:09:30,751 --> 01:09:33,185
So he arrived at Great Yarmouth yesterday

1066
01:09:33,271 --> 01:09:35,910
I was not aware
that Great Yarmouth is a naval port.

1067
01:09:35,991 --> 01:09:38,903
He travelled on the mail packet from Hamburg.

1068
01:09:38,991 --> 01:09:40,424
lsn't that peculiar?

1069
01:09:40,511 --> 01:09:44,106
I should have supposed that a victorious admiral
would arrive on his flagship.

1070
01:09:44,191 --> 01:09:46,830
Flagship? Oh, er...

1071
01:09:47,951 --> 01:09:52,422
It is not customary as you know
for ladies to travel on battleships

1072
01:09:53,471 --> 01:09:54,904
See.

1073
01:09:57,471 --> 01:10:01,942
I wondered why the Admiralty had decided
not to give my husband an official reception.

1074
01:10:02,031 --> 01:10:04,465
Now I understand and fully agree.

1075
01:10:04,551 --> 01:10:08,544
The programme for Lord Nelson's stay
in London will be a simple one.

1076
01:10:08,631 --> 01:10:12,260
He should be able to leave for his home
in Norfolk the day after tomorrow,

1077
01:10:12,351 --> 01:10:13,909
even tomorrow night.

1078
01:10:13,991 --> 01:10:17,108
Do I understand that my husband will be forced
to resign from the Navy?

1079
01:10:17,191 --> 01:10:19,625
Oh, no, no, no, no, Lady Nelson.

1080
01:10:19,711 --> 01:10:21,941
Hardly as drastic as that.

1081
01:10:22,031 --> 01:10:26,866
Extended leave for the benefit of his health
will be suggested.

1082
01:10:26,951 --> 01:10:28,907
A matter of different words.

1083
01:10:28,991 --> 01:10:32,063
That's what you mean, isn't it? I'm glad.

1084
01:10:32,151 --> 01:10:34,540
You were quite right
to spare the people of London.

1085
01:10:34,631 --> 01:10:40,228
The indignity of feting a hero who treats
with contempt the most sacred rules of life.

1086
01:10:42,271 --> 01:10:44,739
May I say a personal word?

1087
01:10:44,831 --> 01:10:47,982
Try to be forgiving, Lady Nelson.

1088
01:10:48,071 --> 01:10:52,747
Only the weaknesses of the great are glaring.

1089
01:10:55,391 --> 01:10:57,347
I prefer the official view.

1090
01:11:00,231 --> 01:11:02,461
Goodbye, Lady Nelson.

1091
01:11:02,551 --> 01:11:04,507
(Cheering outside)

1092
01:11:04,591 --> 01:11:06,149
Did you hear it? Cheering.

1093
01:11:06,231 --> 01:11:08,870
Listen. He's coming! He's coming!

1094
01:11:08,951 --> 01:11:13,581
Excuse me, sir. May I have your permission
to hang a flag in the balcony?

1095
01:11:13,671 --> 01:11:16,629
Hang two flags, three flags,
everything you've got.

1096
01:11:16,711 --> 01:11:20,784
Come on! Come on!
Hang the coat of arms between the flags!

1097
01:11:20,871 --> 01:11:25,740
Most opportune, sir. We saved the coat of arms
from King George's jubilee!

1098
01:11:25,831 --> 01:11:28,709
Do you realise
that these are my private rooms, sir?

1099
01:11:28,791 --> 01:11:31,703
Forgive me, Your Ladyship.
I had no idea this would happen.

1100
01:11:31,791 --> 01:11:36,023
The Admiralty told me that Lord Nelson's return
would be private and without demonstration.

1101
01:11:36,111 --> 01:11:39,820
We never dreamed that the public would
take the matter so completely in hand.

1102
01:11:39,911 --> 01:11:42,789
Has the government no control
over this vulgar demonstration?

1103
01:11:42,871 --> 01:11:46,181
No, ma'am. The vulgar demonstration
has control over the government.

1104
01:11:46,271 --> 01:11:48,227
MR NELSON: Bravo for Nelson! Bravo!

1105
01:11:48,311 --> 01:11:52,702
I must get back to the Admiralty,
hang out all the flags we've got.

1106
01:11:52,791 --> 01:11:54,383
Listen, church bells.

1107
01:11:54,471 --> 01:11:57,269
Victory bells for my son.

1108
01:11:59,911 --> 01:12:01,867
Here they are!

1109
01:12:01,951 --> 01:12:03,907
(Cheering continues)

1110
01:12:07,431 --> 01:12:10,901
Mr Nelson, my name is Hamilton.

1111
01:12:10,991 --> 01:12:14,347
Oh, my son's good friend.
He's often told me about you in his letters.

1112
01:12:14,431 --> 01:12:16,945
You're to be congratulated.
You have a great son.

1113
01:12:17,031 --> 01:12:19,909
Lady Nelson, I am delighted to meet you.

1114
01:12:19,991 --> 01:12:24,189
We had the privilege of joining your husband
in his triumphant procession across Europe.

1115
01:12:24,271 --> 01:12:27,866
It was overwhelming and quite exhausting,
I'm afraid, for an old man.

1116
01:12:27,951 --> 01:12:32,502
My wife was in her element. She swallows
a triumph like a penguin swallows a herring.

1117
01:12:32,591 --> 01:12:34,502
Did you have a good crossing, Sir William?

1118
01:12:34,591 --> 01:12:38,061
Quite rough, I'm afraid. Everyone was seasick
and I was sicker than them all.

1119
01:12:38,151 --> 01:12:40,984
I made the mistake of trying
to ward it off with pills.

1120
01:12:41,071 --> 01:12:44,541
- Oh dear dear
- What's the good of trying to fight the elements?

1121
01:12:44,631 --> 01:12:46,986
It's far more sensible, is it not, Lady Nelson,

1122
01:12:47,071 --> 01:12:49,426
and so much easier to accept their victory

1123
01:12:49,511 --> 01:12:53,390
whether those elements be around us
or within us

1124
01:12:54,471 --> 01:12:58,259
I hope we shall have the pleasure
of seeing your frequently, Lady Nelson.

1125
01:12:58,351 --> 01:13:01,423
He's coming! Nelson! Nelson!

1126
01:13:01,511 --> 01:13:03,467
Bravo for Nelson!

1127
01:13:04,151 --> 01:13:05,823
My boy!

1128
01:13:07,551 --> 01:13:10,827
How proud your mother would be
if she could see you this day.

1129
01:13:10,911 --> 01:13:13,027
How have you been all these years, Father?

1130
01:13:13,111 --> 01:13:15,784
First rate. Fanny's taken great care of me.

1131
01:13:18,911 --> 01:13:20,663
I'm sure she has.

1132
01:13:23,991 --> 01:13:26,266
There is so much I have to be grateful to you for.

1133
01:13:27,511 --> 01:13:29,467
How are you, my dear?

1134
01:13:29,551 --> 01:13:31,303
I'm very well.

1135
01:13:37,271 --> 01:13:38,863
And how is Burnham Thorpe?

1136
01:13:38,951 --> 01:13:40,589
They've named a street after us.

1137
01:13:40,671 --> 01:13:42,070
What an honour.

1138
01:13:42,151 --> 01:13:44,540
(Laughs)
EMMA: Are these Lord Nelson's rooms?

1139
01:13:44,631 --> 01:13:46,303
Yes milady

1140
01:13:46,391 --> 01:13:50,020
It was magnificent, stupendous.
Wasn't it wonderful, William?

1141
01:13:50,111 --> 01:13:53,990
They're wild with enthusiasm.
Come to the balcony! Quickly Quickly!

1142
01:13:54,071 --> 01:13:56,346
(Band plays)? For He's A Jolly Good Fellow

1143
01:14:08,871 --> 01:14:11,146
CROWD:? For he's a jolly good fellow

1144
01:14:11,231 --> 01:14:13,904
? For he's a jolly good fellow

1145
01:14:13,991 --> 01:14:16,744
? For he's a jolly good fellow

1146
01:14:16,831 --> 01:14:18,662
? And so say all of us

1147
01:14:19,111 --> 01:14:20,988
? And so say all of us

1148
01:14:21,471 --> 01:14:23,905
? And so say all of us

1149
01:14:23,991 --> 01:14:26,459
? For he's a jolly good fellow

1150
01:14:26,551 --> 01:14:28,667
? And so say all of us

1151
01:14:29,151 --> 01:14:31,221
? And so say all of us

1152
01:14:31,711 --> 01:14:34,271
? And so say all of us

1153
01:14:34,351 --> 01:14:36,865
? For he's a jolly good fellow

1154
01:14:36,951 --> 01:14:38,145
Lady Nelson...

1155
01:14:38,231 --> 01:14:39,789
? And so say all of us

1156
01:14:39,871 --> 01:14:41,429
I am Emma Hamilton.

1157
01:14:41,511 --> 01:14:45,390
CROWD: Hooray! Hip hip hooray!

1158
01:14:45,471 --> 01:14:46,870
Hip hip hooray!

1159
01:14:47,351 --> 01:14:49,819
Hip hip hooray!

1160
01:14:50,311 --> 01:14:52,666
Hip hip hooray!

1161
01:15:05,231 --> 01:15:07,187
Well, it's been a great day.

1162
01:15:07,271 --> 01:15:09,102
A wonderful day.

1163
01:15:09,191 --> 01:15:12,501
And next month,
it's the choirboys' picnic at Burnham Thorpe.

1164
01:15:12,591 --> 01:15:15,583
(Laughs)
LADY NELSON: Why do you laugh?

1165
01:15:15,671 --> 01:15:18,504
Are the places of country people
of so small account?

1166
01:15:18,591 --> 01:15:22,379
A little more wholesome I think
than the mass hysteria we've seen today

1167
01:15:22,471 --> 01:15:25,747
Well, call it what you like.
It was a beautiful reception.

1168
01:15:25,831 --> 01:15:29,949
MOTHER: You wouldn't believe the fuss
they made about him at Naples after the battle

1169
01:15:30,031 --> 01:15:33,467
Whoo! Such crowds. Thousands of Italians.

1170
01:15:33,551 --> 01:15:35,906
All smelling of different sorts of onions.

1171
01:15:35,991 --> 01:15:37,947
MR NELSON: Onions?

1172
01:15:38,031 --> 01:15:42,821
Yes, they always do. I don't know why,
it comes out more when they get excited.

1173
01:15:42,911 --> 01:15:46,221
There was such a crowd round the embassy
the milkman couldn't get in

1174
01:15:46,311 --> 01:15:48,984
So His Lordship had to go
without his macaroni pudding.

1175
01:15:49,071 --> 01:15:50,470
LADY NELSON: His what?

1176
01:15:50,551 --> 01:15:55,750
My Emma put him on macaroni pudding
to fatten him up after the battle.

1177
01:15:55,831 --> 01:15:58,504
Did you ever meet the King of Naples,
Mrs Nelson?

1178
01:15:59,551 --> 01:16:01,507
He was a one for macaroni.

1179
01:16:01,591 --> 01:16:05,106
He'd take pieces that length,
open his gullet and drop it in.

1180
01:16:05,191 --> 01:16:07,102
Proper caution, he was

1181
01:16:07,191 --> 01:16:10,228
He came to see Emma with the Queen one day
and he pinched my...

1182
01:16:10,311 --> 01:16:11,744
He pinched me.

1183
01:16:11,831 --> 01:16:13,867
He pinched you? The King?

1184
01:16:13,951 --> 01:16:16,545
Well, you see, he's a foreigner, poor King.

1185
01:16:16,631 --> 01:16:22,069
He got so jealous when they cheered
His Lordship because he loved it so himself.

1186
01:16:22,911 --> 01:16:27,701
If you shouted outside his palace,
he'd come in and out like a cuckoo clock.

1187
01:16:27,791 --> 01:16:31,830
Emma... Emma, who was that other king
we met on the way home?

1188
01:16:31,911 --> 01:16:34,983
You know,
I get so mixed up with all these monarchs.

1189
01:16:37,311 --> 01:16:40,383
Oh, dear, Emma. Will you excuse me, dear?
I've been up since five.

1190
01:16:40,471 --> 01:16:43,031
Of course, Mother, darling. Good night.

1191
01:16:43,111 --> 01:16:47,263
Oh, it's good to be back in England again
to hear the Bow Bells and the muffin men

1192
01:16:47,351 --> 01:16:49,501
and the soot falling down your chimney.

1193
01:16:49,591 --> 01:16:51,547
(Mother laughs)

1194
01:16:58,311 --> 01:17:01,189
MR NELSON: Well Sir William
how goes the world these days?

1195
01:17:01,271 --> 01:17:03,580
Can we hope for a little peace now?

1196
01:17:03,671 --> 01:17:05,229
Well, I don't know.

1197
01:17:05,311 --> 01:17:07,984
What was that medicine you gave my husband?

1198
01:17:08,071 --> 01:17:11,825
It's some stuff my mother makes.
It's very good for coughs and colds.

1199
01:17:11,911 --> 01:17:14,584
I think I would prefer my husband
to see a doctor.

1200
01:17:15,631 --> 01:17:17,587
This weather is dreadful for him.

1201
01:17:17,671 --> 01:17:21,346
It was so different in Italy.
The sun always seemed to shine there.

1202
01:17:21,431 --> 01:17:24,821
Yes, it's never very agreeable
in the Thames Valley during the winter.

1203
01:17:24,911 --> 01:17:28,950
It's only for a few days. Once he's back
in Norfolk, he'll be a different man.

1204
01:17:29,031 --> 01:17:31,499
Do you think
you will be leaving London so soon?

1205
01:17:31,591 --> 01:17:33,866
Certainly. There's nothing to detain us.

1206
01:17:33,951 --> 01:17:38,229
Directly he's made his report to the Admiralty
and taken his seat in the House of Lords,

1207
01:17:38,311 --> 01:17:39,664
we shall be free to go.

1208
01:17:39,751 --> 01:17:41,230
Why not?

1209
01:17:41,311 --> 01:17:43,267
Oh...of course, yes.

1210
01:17:43,351 --> 01:17:45,307
What are your plans, Lady Hamilton?

1211
01:17:45,391 --> 01:17:47,905
I suppose you'll be going abroad again shortly?

1212
01:17:47,991 --> 01:17:51,870
We don't really know.
Life is so very uncertain, isn't it?

1213
01:17:51,951 --> 01:17:53,907
I haven't found it so.

1214
01:17:55,551 --> 01:17:59,305
Will you excuse me, Lady Hamilton?
It's been a very exhausting day.

1215
01:17:59,391 --> 01:18:01,461
- Of course. Good night.
- Good night.

1216
01:18:15,031 --> 01:18:16,430
Emma.

1217
01:18:19,111 --> 01:18:21,067
We've been living in a dream.

1218
01:18:22,111 --> 01:18:25,626
And now we are faced with the truth,
how ugly it is.

1219
01:18:25,711 --> 01:18:27,144
How terribly ugly.

1220
01:18:27,231 --> 01:18:29,461
But we've still got the courage to face it.

1221
01:18:29,551 --> 01:18:32,019
What's the good of being courageous
if you're trapped?

1222
01:18:32,111 --> 01:18:34,386
If you know you are wrong
and there's no way out.

1223
01:18:36,031 --> 01:18:39,944
I'll go to her and talk to her. Tonight. At once.

1224
01:18:40,031 --> 01:18:42,465
And you must talk to William.

1225
01:18:42,551 --> 01:18:44,507
They must understand

1226
01:18:44,591 --> 01:18:46,547
- Divorce?
- There is no other way

1227
01:18:46,631 --> 01:18:48,189
No, m y ove

1228
01:18:48,271 --> 01:18:51,422
That might be well enough for other people,
but not for you.

1229
01:18:51,511 --> 01:18:55,709
You are not an ordinary man and you cannot
behave like a Mr Jones or a Mr Thompson.

1230
01:18:55,791 --> 01:18:57,747
I wish I were a Mr Thompson.

1231
01:18:57,831 --> 01:19:01,585
Now, for the first time,
I begin to understand what William meant.

1232
01:19:01,671 --> 01:19:03,980
What we're doing is so dreadfully wrong.

1233
01:19:04,071 --> 01:19:06,585
Of course, I should have realised it before.

1234
01:19:06,671 --> 01:19:09,629
And because it is wrong,
it cannot bring happiness.

1235
01:19:11,471 --> 01:19:13,427
Those streets we came along today.

1236
01:19:13,511 --> 01:19:18,380
They're the very same streets I walked through
when I was a kitchen maid looking for work,

1237
01:19:18,471 --> 01:19:21,110
but, today, they were the scene of your triumph,

1238
01:19:21,191 --> 01:19:24,103
the triumph of our greatest man
coming to his home.

1239
01:19:25,231 --> 01:19:28,701
They have made you the symbol
of all that is most precious to them.

1240
01:19:28,791 --> 01:19:31,351
Whatever you do
will be their guide and example.

1241
01:19:31,431 --> 01:19:33,581
You will not speak to your wife

1242
01:19:33,671 --> 01:19:35,980
and I shall not speak to William.

1243
01:19:36,071 --> 01:19:38,346
(Clock chimes)

1244
01:19:42,071 --> 01:19:43,743
I'm cold!

1245
01:19:43,831 --> 01:19:45,901
I'm freezing. I'm frightened!

1246
01:19:45,991 --> 01:19:48,551
Emma! Somebody will hear you.

1247
01:19:48,631 --> 01:19:50,587
Ssh, Emma!

1248
01:19:50,671 --> 01:19:52,423
Dear, Emma, ssh!

1249
01:19:53,471 --> 01:19:57,020
(Whispers) Is this better?
Lowered voices? Stolen meetings?

1250
01:19:58,071 --> 01:20:00,631
Darkness, suspicion, lies, more lies?

1251
01:20:02,071 --> 01:20:04,027
Is this what has become of it?

1252
01:20:04,111 --> 01:20:06,067
All that beauty

1253
01:20:06,151 --> 01:20:08,301
and light and glory?

1254
01:20:12,071 --> 01:20:14,221
Good night, my dearest love.

1255
01:20:18,671 --> 01:20:20,229
Good night.

1256
01:20:24,071 --> 01:20:26,027
(Sobs)

1257
01:20:32,071 --> 01:20:34,027
(Clock chimes)

1258
01:20:36,871 --> 01:20:38,827
I, my lords,

1259
01:20:38,911 --> 01:20:41,584
have, in different countries,

1260
01:20:41,671 --> 01:20:44,629
seen much of the miseries of war.

1261
01:20:45,751 --> 01:20:47,707
I am, therefore,

1262
01:20:47,791 --> 01:20:49,747
in my innermost soul...

1263
01:20:50,831 --> 01:20:52,787
..a man of peace.

1264
01:20:54,071 --> 01:20:58,189
Yet I would not, for the sake of any peace,

1265
01:20:58,271 --> 01:21:00,580
however fortunate,

1266
01:21:00,671 --> 01:21:03,105
consent to sacrifice

1267
01:21:03,191 --> 01:21:06,740
one jot of England's honour.

1268
01:21:06,831 --> 01:21:08,583
Hitherto

1269
01:21:08,671 --> 01:21:12,550
there has been nothing greater known
on the continent

1270
01:21:12,631 --> 01:21:14,587
than the faith

1271
01:21:14,671 --> 01:21:16,946
the untainted honour

1272
01:21:17,031 --> 01:21:20,387
the generous public sympathies

1273
01:21:20,471 --> 01:21:22,939
the high diplomatic influence,

1274
01:21:23,031 --> 01:21:24,987
the commerce,

1275
01:21:25,071 --> 01:21:27,027
the grandeur,

1276
01:21:27,111 --> 01:21:29,067
the irresistible power,

1277
01:21:29,151 --> 01:21:32,507
the unconquerable valour of the British nation.

1278
01:21:32,591 --> 01:21:34,547
(Murmurs of agreement)

1279
01:21:35,671 --> 01:21:39,027
He's nervous.
Look. Look at his hand. He's trembling.

1280
01:21:39,111 --> 01:21:43,582
It's nerve-racking for any man
to come into the House of Lords for the first time.

1281
01:21:43,671 --> 01:21:47,141
It will be more nerve-racking
for the poor man when he goes out.

1282
01:21:47,231 --> 01:21:48,983
Why?

1283
01:21:49,071 --> 01:21:51,027
There is that Hamilton woman.

1284
01:21:51,111 --> 01:21:54,547
peace or war no interest

1285
01:21:55,671 --> 01:21:58,026
And, don't look now, his wife.

1286
01:21:59,071 --> 01:22:03,030
and as the nation was pleased
with the sincere spirit of peace

1287
01:22:03,111 --> 01:22:06,990
It will be a thrilling moment
when he goes into the vestibule.

1288
01:22:07,071 --> 01:22:10,268
I can hardly wait
to see which one he goes to first.

1289
01:22:10,351 --> 01:22:11,909
Her?

1290
01:22:11,991 --> 01:22:13,947
Or her?

1291
01:22:27,631 --> 01:22:29,428
Here he comes.

1292
01:22:50,831 --> 01:22:52,822
My dear, were you comfortable up there?

1293
01:22:52,911 --> 01:22:54,947
Sufficiently, Horatio. Sufficiently.

1294
01:22:55,031 --> 01:22:57,465
- Did you hear my speech?
- For the most part.

1295
01:22:57,551 --> 01:23:00,907
You have a way of overemphasising,
which is rather embarrassing.

1296
01:23:00,991 --> 01:23:02,947
- Oh.
- It was quite interesting.

1297
01:23:03,031 --> 01:23:04,464
Lady Keith.

1298
01:23:04,551 --> 01:23:05,984
Lady Spencer.

1299
01:23:06,071 --> 01:23:07,629
Lady Hamilton.

1300
01:23:14,151 --> 01:23:16,107
WOMAN: Why, what's the matter?

1301
01:23:16,191 --> 01:23:19,547
GENTLEMAN: Stand back please! Give her air!
- What was that?

1302
01:23:19,631 --> 01:23:21,747
- It's Lady Hamilton!
- Stand back please!

1303
01:23:21,831 --> 01:23:23,867
Wait, Frances, please.

1304
01:23:23,951 --> 01:23:26,101
- Will you fetch a doctor?
- Immediately.

1305
01:23:27,591 --> 01:23:29,024
Make way, please

1306
01:23:29,111 --> 01:23:31,227
- What's happened?
- I told her not to come.

1307
01:23:31,311 --> 01:23:33,063
She's not been feeling well all day.

1308
01:23:33,151 --> 01:23:34,982
N SO N W here s the doctor?

1309
01:23:35,071 --> 01:23:36,823
But why should she faint?

1310
01:23:36,911 --> 01:23:39,584
My dear, it's natural to women of all classes.

1311
01:23:39,671 --> 01:23:41,229
Drive on!

1312
01:23:44,071 --> 01:23:45,424
(Door opens)

1313
01:23:45,511 --> 01:23:46,660
Well?

1314
01:23:46,751 --> 01:23:50,983
Frances, how could you drive away like that,
without making the slightest effort to help?

1315
01:23:51,071 --> 01:23:53,187
Did you expect me to take her into my carriage,

1316
01:23:53,271 --> 01:23:56,263
just because she selects the House of Lords
for her melodrama?

1317
01:23:56,351 --> 01:24:00,230
When people have been kind to me and
generous, don't ignore them when they're ill.

1318
01:24:00,311 --> 01:24:02,586
- Even in the House of Lords.
- Generous? Ha ha!

1319
01:24:02,671 --> 01:24:05,185
It is well known that what success
I may have achieved

1320
01:24:05,271 --> 01:24:08,468
has been largely due
to the help I have received from the Hamiltons.

1321
01:24:08,551 --> 01:24:10,906
- Why are you so ungrateful?
- Why are you so blind?

1322
01:24:10,991 --> 01:24:12,947
Don't you see what that woman is after?

1323
01:24:13,031 --> 01:24:16,944
It's the oldest story in the world,
the most sordid and the most contemptible.

1324
01:24:17,031 --> 01:24:20,990
Find a public hero and there you'll find,
as sure as fate, a woman parasite.

1325
01:24:21,071 --> 01:24:24,381
Don't you realise that all she wants
is to flutter about in your glory,

1326
01:24:24,471 --> 01:24:26,507
to use you for her own ambition and conceit?

1327
01:24:26,591 --> 01:24:28,980
Oh, I know, she helped you,
she encouraged you.

1328
01:24:29,071 --> 01:24:31,665
Why, it was part of her plan
to play upon your vanity.

1329
01:24:31,751 --> 01:24:34,265
She's capable of declaring you
the father of her child.

1330
01:24:34,351 --> 01:24:36,307
- Frances, control yourself!
- Why not?

1331
01:24:36,391 --> 01:24:38,621
Even that accusation stirs some men's vanities.

1332
01:24:38,711 --> 01:24:39,666
Silence!

1333
01:24:39,751 --> 01:24:42,219
Oh, yes, everyone says
she's a wonderful actress.

1334
01:24:42,311 --> 01:24:45,587
She is brilliant, to have hidden
her sweet secret for so long.

1335
01:24:45,671 --> 01:24:49,823
The other day, you remarked upon
the new fashions, all these frills and folds.

1336
01:24:49,911 --> 01:24:52,869
She invented them and all society followed.

1337
01:24:52,951 --> 01:24:56,102
Wonderful to lead society into helping her
through a predicament.

1338
01:24:56,191 --> 01:25:00,025
You fool! Don't you realise everything she does
is calculated and cold-blooded?

1339
01:25:00,111 --> 01:25:02,466
She faints in the House of Lords,
a perfect place.

1340
01:25:02,551 --> 01:25:05,782
Do you suppose she'd have wasted time
in fainting in her own bedroom?

1341
01:25:05,871 --> 01:25:07,623
You poor silly man!

1342
01:25:09,071 --> 01:25:10,823
Poor and silly?

1343
01:25:11,871 --> 01:25:14,101
Yes, that is what I am without her.

1344
01:25:14,191 --> 01:25:16,580
I'm a peer of England because of her.

1345
01:25:16,671 --> 01:25:19,105
And because of her, I'm Lady Nelson.

1346
01:25:20,151 --> 01:25:22,301
Lady Nelson? Ha!

1347
01:25:22,391 --> 01:25:24,347
What an honour!

1348
01:25:24,431 --> 01:25:28,743
They point after my coach, point up
at my windows, point at me in the streets.

1349
01:25:28,831 --> 01:25:31,299
There's a coarse joke about me in the taverns.

1350
01:25:31,391 --> 01:25:33,825
A foul song about me on the Limehouse barges.

1351
01:25:33,911 --> 01:25:35,663
Lady Nelson!

1352
01:25:35,751 --> 01:25:37,309
How funny!

1353
01:25:37,391 --> 01:25:39,143
How pitiful!

1354
01:25:40,191 --> 01:25:42,147
And how proud I might have been.

1355
01:25:43,551 --> 01:25:45,621
I'm sorry, Frances.

1356
01:25:46,871 --> 01:25:48,429
Sorry?

1357
01:25:48,511 --> 01:25:50,467
Is that all you have to give me?

1358
01:25:51,591 --> 01:25:54,151
Yes. That is all.

1359
01:25:54,231 --> 01:25:55,983
Very well.

1360
01:25:56,071 --> 01:25:59,620
I shall take that as your answer
and now you shall have mine.

1361
01:25:59,711 --> 01:26:01,463
I shall go away,

1362
01:26:01,551 --> 01:26:05,510
but I shall never drag the name of Nelson
through the divorce court.

1363
01:26:05,591 --> 01:26:08,025
As long as I live, I shall be your wife.

1364
01:26:08,111 --> 01:26:09,669
Goodbye.

1365
01:26:20,391 --> 01:26:22,541
Horatio, call her back.

1366
01:26:22,631 --> 01:26:25,225
I implore you, call her back.

1367
01:26:25,311 --> 01:26:27,745
You mustn't let her go like this.

1368
01:26:29,311 --> 01:26:31,825
I couldn't help hearing what you said, Horatio.

1369
01:26:31,911 --> 01:26:33,469
Please, Father,

1370
01:26:33,551 --> 01:26:35,507
try to understand.

1371
01:26:35,591 --> 01:26:37,547
do, m y boy, do

1372
01:26:37,631 --> 01:26:41,909
I know I'm a silly old man, a humble
country parson, and I don't know the world,

1373
01:26:41,991 --> 01:26:45,267
except the little people who come to me with
their little troubles,

1374
01:26:45,351 --> 01:26:49,742
but even those little people sometimes
have to fight in the depths of their soul,

1375
01:26:49,831 --> 01:26:53,585
the same temptations as you,
the great of the world.

1376
01:26:53,671 --> 01:26:56,868
And, when they have to choose
between right and wrong,

1377
01:26:56,951 --> 01:26:59,829
I give them the same advice
as I give to you now.

1378
01:26:59,911 --> 01:27:04,507
Even if it forces all three of us
to live in misery for the rest of our lives?

1379
01:27:04,591 --> 01:27:06,343
Even so.

1380
01:27:07,391 --> 01:27:09,461
That is something I cannot do, Father.

1381
01:27:11,271 --> 01:27:13,227
Then I shall go with her, Horatio.

1382
01:27:17,631 --> 01:27:19,587
What s the name off the child?

1383
01:27:19,671 --> 01:27:21,627
Horatia Thompson.

1384
01:27:23,071 --> 01:27:25,027
Her father's name?

1385
01:27:25,111 --> 01:27:27,067
Horatio Thompson.

1386
01:27:30,751 --> 01:27:32,901
- Profession?
- Sailor.

1387
01:27:35,951 --> 01:27:37,703
Where is he now?

1388
01:27:37,791 --> 01:27:39,349
At sea.

1389
01:27:47,351 --> 01:27:49,307
(Running footsteps)

1390
01:27:51,511 --> 01:27:53,467
- Emily!
- Mother, darling!

1391
01:27:53,551 --> 01:27:55,587
- Are you well?
- Yes. How's the baby?

1392
01:27:55,671 --> 01:27:59,266
I wish you could see her. She's an angel.
Not at all like a child of two months.

1393
01:27:59,351 --> 01:28:00,943
She's like a little princess.

1394
01:28:01,031 --> 01:28:05,149
I wish you could see the way she receives
her bottle and then indicates the meal is over.

1395
01:28:05,231 --> 01:28:07,506
- You'd adore her.
- What does she weigh now?

1396
01:28:07,591 --> 01:28:09,707
9lb 4oz, before her second bottle.

1397
01:28:09,791 --> 01:28:11,782
- The news, isn't it splendid?
- What news?

1398
01:28:11,871 --> 01:28:14,146
- Haven't you heard?
- I haven't been out

1399
01:28:14,231 --> 01:28:18,463
He's done it again. He's beaten the Danes.
It's a glorious victory!

1400
01:28:18,551 --> 01:28:21,588
Nelson was in the front line of battle,
ahead of the main fleet.

1401
01:28:21,671 --> 01:28:25,266
His commander in chief saw the enemy
outnumbered us by more than two to one.

1402
01:28:25,351 --> 01:28:28,502
He sent off a signal to Nelson
telling him to give up and withdraw.

1403
01:28:28,591 --> 01:28:32,266
Do you know what Nelson did?
When the signal was pointed out to him,

1404
01:28:32,351 --> 01:28:37,141
he put a telescope to his blind eye, said, ''I'm
darned if I can see it'', went on fighting and won.

1405
01:28:37,231 --> 01:28:42,305
There, you see, everything comes in handy,
if you know how to use it, even a blind eye!

1406
01:28:42,391 --> 01:28:44,347
(Both giggle)

1407
01:28:45,391 --> 01:28:47,507
How's William, Mother?

1408
01:28:47,591 --> 01:28:51,186
I have some news, too, Emma,
but not so good as yours.

1409
01:28:51,271 --> 01:28:56,220
All his treasures, pictures, everything, he's
waited for them to come from Naples for so long.

1410
01:28:56,311 --> 01:29:00,668
Now, we know for certain they all went down
in the ship that was lost in the storm.

1411
01:29:00,751 --> 01:29:03,982
Oh, poor William. That was his whole life.

1412
01:29:05,111 --> 01:29:06,669
Gavin,

1413
01:29:06,751 --> 01:29:08,707
that picture, there,

1414
01:29:08,791 --> 01:29:10,588
the Van Dyck.

1415
01:29:10,671 --> 01:29:12,627
It's crooked, don't you see?

1416
01:29:13,671 --> 01:29:15,707
I've told you about it twice already.

1417
01:29:15,791 --> 01:29:18,624
- Why don't you put it straight?
- Yes, Sir William.

1418
01:29:25,071 --> 01:29:27,027
- Here, sir?
- Yes.

1419
01:29:28,671 --> 01:29:30,229
That's good.

1420
01:29:30,311 --> 01:29:31,869
Good, Gavin.

1421
01:29:32,911 --> 01:29:35,584
It's good to have my pictures
around me once more

1422
01:29:35,671 --> 01:29:37,627
and my statues.

1423
01:29:37,711 --> 01:29:40,987
But they... They need more light, more room.

1424
01:29:41,071 --> 01:29:43,301
We must rearrange them, Gavin.

1425
01:29:49,071 --> 01:29:50,823
Gavin...

1426
01:29:50,911 --> 01:29:53,664
I'll dine with Miss Hart tonight.

1427
01:29:53,751 --> 01:29:55,309
Alone.

1428
01:29:55,391 --> 01:29:57,347
At eight o'clock.

1429
01:30:02,471 --> 01:30:05,429
Look after yourself.
Talk to Sir William before it's too late.

1430
01:30:05,511 --> 01:30:08,981
Or the house itseIf will go to his nephew
instead of to his wife.

1431
01:30:09,071 --> 01:30:11,824
His wife?
Why, I have never been his wife, Mother.

1432
01:30:11,911 --> 01:30:13,867
Let Charles have the money.

1433
01:30:13,951 --> 01:30:16,226
I don't want it and I don't deserve it.

1434
01:30:16,311 --> 01:30:21,431
But, my darling, if things stay as they are,
you won't have a penny when he dies.

1435
01:30:21,511 --> 01:30:23,467
You'll be poor!

1436
01:30:23,551 --> 01:30:25,507
I shall be rich.

1437
01:30:25,591 --> 01:30:28,344
I've got my child, his child.

1438
01:30:28,431 --> 01:30:31,707
I think that means more
than all the money in the world.

1439
01:30:35,351 --> 01:30:39,424
- Can I see Sir William now, Gavin?
- I don't think it's advisable, milady.

1440
01:30:39,511 --> 01:30:42,264
He's sleeping, very peacefully.

1441
01:30:56,071 --> 01:30:58,824
Gentlemen, the victor of Copenhagen!

1442
01:30:58,911 --> 01:31:00,867
ALL: Bravo, Nelson!

1443
01:31:07,071 --> 01:31:12,623
Lord Nelson, your decisive defeat of the Danes
has made it possible for the British Government

1444
01:31:12,711 --> 01:31:17,546
to negotiate this honourable
and, I must say, unexpected peace with France.

1445
01:31:17,631 --> 01:31:21,180
We all believe, with the deepest conviction,

1446
01:31:21,271 --> 01:31:23,990
that we shall have, at last, peace.

1447
01:31:24,071 --> 01:31:26,027
ALL: Hear, hear!

1448
01:31:27,751 --> 01:31:29,548
Lord Spencer,

1449
01:31:29,631 --> 01:31:31,189
gentlemen...

1450
01:31:32,311 --> 01:31:36,748
..you are celebrating a peace
with Napoleon Bonaparte.

1451
01:31:38,351 --> 01:31:40,307
''Peace'' is a very beautiful word,

1452
01:31:40,391 --> 01:31:42,746
as long as the impulse of peace is behind it,

1453
01:31:42,831 --> 01:31:45,265
but you will never make peace with Napoleon.

1454
01:31:45,351 --> 01:31:47,307
He doesn't mean peace, today.

1455
01:31:48,351 --> 01:31:50,581
He just wants to gain a little time...

1456
01:31:51,631 --> 01:31:53,587
..to rearm himseIf at sea

1457
01:31:53,671 --> 01:31:57,220
and make new alliances with Italy and Spain,
all to one purpose.

1458
01:31:57,311 --> 01:31:59,825
To destroy our empire!

1459
01:31:59,911 --> 01:32:03,062
Years ago, I said the same thing at Naples.

1460
01:32:03,151 --> 01:32:07,702
I begged them, entreated them, not to give way,
but they wouldn't listen to me and paid the price.

1461
01:32:07,791 --> 01:32:12,546
That was a little kingdom,
miles away in the Mediterranean.

1462
01:32:14,391 --> 01:32:17,349
But now it is England, our own land.

1463
01:32:18,391 --> 01:32:21,747
Napoleon can never be master of the world
until he has smashed us up

1464
01:32:21,831 --> 01:32:25,028
and, believe me, gentlemen,
he means to be master of the world!

1465
01:32:25,111 --> 01:32:27,181
You cannot make peace with dictators.

1466
01:32:27,271 --> 01:32:29,546
You have to destroy them, wipe them out!

1467
01:32:29,631 --> 01:32:33,510
Gentlemen, I implore you,
speak to the Prime Minister before it is too late!

1468
01:32:33,591 --> 01:32:35,547
Do not ratify this peace!

1469
01:32:36,591 --> 01:32:39,389
We, er, appreciate all you say.

1470
01:32:39,471 --> 01:32:43,669
Well, thank you, gentlemen.
I feIt it my duty to tell you of these things.

1471
01:32:43,751 --> 01:32:46,106
I'm not a statesman, of course.

1472
01:32:46,191 --> 01:32:48,147
I'm no diplomat.

1473
01:32:48,231 --> 01:32:50,426
I must leave it in your hands.

1474
01:32:50,511 --> 01:32:52,502
- Gentlemen.
- Good day, Lord Nelson.

1475
01:32:53,551 --> 01:32:55,507
(Heated discussion)

1476
01:32:55,591 --> 01:32:58,901
Going to your, er, home in Norfolk, Nelson?

1477
01:32:58,991 --> 01:33:00,947
I don't... I don't think so.

1478
01:33:02,071 --> 01:33:05,143
My wife tells me
she saw Lady Nelson at Bath, recently.

1479
01:33:05,231 --> 01:33:07,187
Yes. She's very well.

1480
01:33:07,271 --> 01:33:09,705
She gives her time to social work.

1481
01:33:09,791 --> 01:33:12,544
Ah. And er...shall you go to Venice?

1482
01:33:13,591 --> 01:33:15,547
Er... Why Venice?

1483
01:33:15,631 --> 01:33:18,020
Oh, something I heard the other day.

1484
01:33:18,111 --> 01:33:22,901
A little party to some musical festival,
Lady Hamilton and a few English friends.

1485
01:33:23,991 --> 01:33:25,947
Where did you hear this?

1486
01:33:26,031 --> 01:33:29,990
It was that little musical chap,
who came over to Covent Garden to conduct.

1487
01:33:30,071 --> 01:33:33,586
I heard him say something about
Lady Hamilton going back with him

1488
01:33:33,671 --> 01:33:35,229
Oh, well...

1489
01:33:35,311 --> 01:33:37,461
I daresay I've got it all mixed up.

1490
01:33:37,551 --> 01:33:39,781
Well, it's good to see you home again.

1491
01:33:42,071 --> 01:33:44,027
Why, your lordship!

1492
01:33:44,111 --> 01:33:46,067
Good afternoon, Mrs Cadogan.

1493
01:33:46,151 --> 01:33:47,948
Sit down, please.

1494
01:33:48,031 --> 01:33:49,987
Everything is in such a mess.

1495
01:33:50,071 --> 01:33:52,869
Why this sudden move
from Piccadilly to Nero's Hotel?

1496
01:33:52,951 --> 01:33:59,106
Well, you see, everything was so dull and dismal
since William died.

1497
01:33:59,191 --> 01:34:01,147
Emma couldn't stand it any longer.

1498
01:34:01,231 --> 01:34:03,142
see

1499
01:34:03,231 --> 01:34:04,630
Where is she now?

1500
01:34:04,711 --> 01:34:06,667
She went out quite early.

1501
01:34:06,751 --> 01:34:11,427
With the little foreign musical gentleman.
They're... They're driving in the park.

1502
01:34:11,511 --> 01:34:12,660
Oh.

1503
01:34:12,751 --> 01:34:15,026
May wat?
Yes please.

1504
01:34:15,111 --> 01:34:17,579
Look at the flowers. Aren't they pretty?

1505
01:34:17,671 --> 01:34:20,105
So nice for a young widow.

1506
01:34:20,191 --> 01:34:22,147
- Yes.
EMMA: Horatio

1507
01:34:22,231 --> 01:34:24,142
I'm so sorry. Have you been here long?

1508
01:34:24,231 --> 01:34:25,869
Oh, no.

1509
01:34:25,951 --> 01:34:28,511
Emma, dear. I just came in by chance.

1510
01:34:28,591 --> 01:34:32,300
Your mother has been telling me
why you moved from Piccadilly.

1511
01:34:32,391 --> 01:34:33,949
I think you're quite right.

1512
01:34:34,031 --> 01:34:35,987
It was so very gloomy there.

1513
01:34:37,031 --> 01:34:40,341
I haven't seen a great deal of you
since I've been back, Emma.

1514
01:34:40,431 --> 01:34:43,787
- You know what it's like. There's so much to do.
- How is the child?

1515
01:34:43,871 --> 01:34:46,385
I've been meaning every day this week
to go and see her.

1516
01:34:46,471 --> 01:34:48,666
But it's so difficult. It takes almost a whole day.

1517
01:34:48,751 --> 01:34:51,504
Emma, let us drive out
and see her this afternoon.

1518
01:34:51,591 --> 01:34:53,104
Oh, yes.

1519
01:34:53,191 --> 01:34:56,900
Lord Nelson, whom the whole of London knows,
calling on little Horatia Thompson.

1520
01:34:56,991 --> 01:34:58,947
whose father no-one has as yet seen.

1521
01:34:59,031 --> 01:35:01,750
My dear, what a titbit
for Lady Spencer's next dinner party.

1522
01:35:01,831 --> 01:35:02,900
(Knocking)

1523
01:35:02,991 --> 01:35:04,709
Come in.

1524
01:35:06,791 --> 01:35:08,463
Thank you.

1525
01:35:15,471 --> 01:35:19,020
My dear, I know you're very busy
and I don't want to intrude upon your affairs,

1526
01:35:19,111 --> 01:35:22,262
but there are things that I don't quite understand
since I came back

1527
01:35:22,351 --> 01:35:24,069
and to be honest I don't quite like

1528
01:35:24,151 --> 01:35:25,345
What things do you mean?

1529
01:35:25,431 --> 01:35:27,262
Three times this week I've tried to see you

1530
01:35:27,351 --> 01:35:30,548
and each time you've had appointments
with people whom I don't know.

1531
01:35:31,991 --> 01:35:33,947
We had no secrets at one time.

1532
01:35:35,111 --> 01:35:36,430
Even in our letters.

1533
01:35:37,591 --> 01:35:40,185
You surely do not ask to see all my letters.

1534
01:35:41,351 --> 01:35:43,626
Certainly I do not ask to see them, my dear.

1535
01:35:44,671 --> 01:35:46,389
If you want to hide them from me.

1536
01:35:47,431 --> 01:35:48,705
You're jealous!

1537
01:35:48,791 --> 01:35:50,190
Why do you make fun of me?

1538
01:35:50,271 --> 01:35:52,626
Fun? I've never been so happy in all my life.

1539
01:35:52,711 --> 01:35:54,463
You're splendid when you're jealous.

1540
01:35:54,551 --> 01:35:56,985
You must promise me to be jealous always,
please.

1541
01:35:58,511 --> 01:36:01,105
We were talking about some letters, weren't we?

1542
01:36:03,391 --> 01:36:09,785
Horatio, if there are certain letters I would
sooner keep to myself, won't you trust me?

1543
01:36:11,631 --> 01:36:13,383
What are those letters?

1544
01:36:15,911 --> 01:36:17,139
Very well.

1545
01:36:22,151 --> 01:36:24,107
Read them.

1546
01:36:31,271 --> 01:36:33,227
(She plays)

1547
01:36:36,671 --> 01:36:38,229
I'm sorry.

1548
01:36:38,311 --> 01:36:40,267
Forgive me.

1549
01:36:41,111 --> 01:36:43,579
- I'll see you later.
-No, Horatio, don't go.

1550
01:36:45,071 --> 01:36:47,904
You know what will happen
if you leave them unopened.

1551
01:36:47,991 --> 01:36:50,459
We shall never quite understand each other
again.

1552
01:36:50,551 --> 01:36:53,019
They're quite short, and to the point.

1553
01:36:53,111 --> 01:36:55,067
Bills, bills, and more bills.

1554
01:36:55,151 --> 01:36:58,621
Threats, summonses and lawsuits.
I'm up to my neck in them - drowned in them.

1555
01:36:58,711 --> 01:37:01,942
Why do you think I left Piccadilly?
My dear, they threw me out.

1556
01:37:02,031 --> 01:37:04,704
And why do you think
I haven't seen our child for two weeks?

1557
01:37:04,791 --> 01:37:06,941
Because I owe Mrs Gibson
15 guineas for the rent.

1558
01:37:07,031 --> 01:37:09,784
Do you think I like going out
with that little man from Venice?

1559
01:37:09,871 --> 01:37:11,350
I hate the sight of him

1560
01:37:11,431 --> 01:37:14,741
But I have to do it because he's promised me
a contract at his opera house.

1561
01:37:14,831 --> 01:37:16,708
Yes, I'm going back to work.

1562
01:37:16,791 --> 01:37:18,622
I've done it before and I can do it again.

1563
01:37:18,711 --> 01:37:20,383
I don't really mind.

1564
01:37:20,471 --> 01:37:22,939
You see, Horatio,
William didn't leave me a farthing.

1565
01:37:23,031 --> 01:37:25,101
- Why wasn't I told?
- Why should you be told?

1566
01:37:25,191 --> 01:37:26,863
These are my troubles, not yours.

1567
01:37:26,951 --> 01:37:29,784
I've never asked anyone for money
and I never shall.

1568
01:37:29,871 --> 01:37:30,747
Indeed?

1569
01:37:30,831 --> 01:37:32,787
Then are you out of your senses?

1570
01:37:34,711 --> 01:37:37,145
Now, you listen to me, and don't answer back!

1571
01:37:37,991 --> 01:37:40,027
How dare you keep those bills from me.

1572
01:37:40,111 --> 01:37:42,067
Aren't your worries my worries?

1573
01:37:42,151 --> 01:37:44,107
Everything I have is yours.

1574
01:37:44,191 --> 01:37:46,147
Everything!

1575
01:37:49,191 --> 01:37:51,261
You're going to have a home of your own.

1576
01:37:51,351 --> 01:37:54,627
And there is going to be no sorrow
and no trouble ever again.

1577
01:37:55,911 --> 01:37:57,469
Emma.

1578
01:37:57,551 --> 01:37:58,540
Dear Emma.

1579
01:38:08,111 --> 01:38:11,148
Mm, that's the best drop of rum I've tasted
since the old days.

1580
01:38:11,231 --> 01:38:14,507
We don't get much excuse to open a bottle
lately. You should come oftener.

1581
01:38:14,591 --> 01:38:17,025
It warms the cockles of your heart. (Laughs)

1582
01:38:19,071 --> 01:38:22,381
Captain Hardy, how nice to see you again.

1583
01:38:22,471 --> 01:38:24,143
Why didn't you tell us you were coming?

1584
01:38:24,231 --> 01:38:28,349
Well, to tell you the truth, I just happened to be
passing and thought I'd come and see you.

1585
01:38:28,431 --> 01:38:29,705
Will you stay to luncheon?

1586
01:38:29,791 --> 01:38:31,702
Oh, thank you, my lady.

1587
01:38:31,791 --> 01:38:35,579
Mother, darling, tell the coachman we leave
at two. I want the child here before dark.

1588
01:38:35,671 --> 01:38:36,865
Yes, dear, I'll tell him.

1589
01:38:36,951 --> 01:38:39,863
He's in the garden. You can see his work of art
in the summerhouse.

1590
01:38:39,951 --> 01:38:43,307
I don't want to disturb him, my lady.
I know he likes his peace and quiet.

1591
01:38:43,391 --> 01:38:47,100
Just because he won't see St Vincent and Keith
when they write him pompous letters?

1592
01:38:47,191 --> 01:38:48,670
Oh, no, Hardy, you're different.

1593
01:38:48,751 --> 01:38:50,230
You're an old friend. Come along.

1594
01:38:50,311 --> 01:38:53,781
No, to tell you the truth, Lady Hamilton,
I didn't come to see him.

1595
01:38:53,871 --> 01:38:55,509
I came to see you.

1596
01:38:55,591 --> 01:38:57,547
Me?
Yes.

1597
01:39:03,071 --> 01:39:05,904
There's no chance of our being overheard,
is there?

1598
01:39:05,991 --> 01:39:08,221
No, but what is the mystery?

1599
01:39:08,311 --> 01:39:11,986
Well, do you ever read the newspapers
down here?

1600
01:39:12,071 --> 01:39:13,868
Not unless we can help it.

1601
01:39:13,951 --> 01:39:16,624
We're not particularly interested
in the court news.

1602
01:39:16,711 --> 01:39:18,349
Nor the gossip, the scandal.

1603
01:39:18,431 --> 01:39:22,026
You may have missed what happened.
Bonaparte's made himseIf Emperor of France.

1604
01:39:23,031 --> 01:39:24,783
Yes, we saw that.

1605
01:39:24,871 --> 01:39:26,224
What is his next move?

1606
01:39:26,311 --> 01:39:28,347
His next move will be the invasion of England.

1607
01:39:29,151 --> 01:39:30,743
Oh, ridiculous!

1608
01:39:30,831 --> 01:39:32,150
So it may sound, my lady.

1609
01:39:32,231 --> 01:39:36,110
That's what we all thought when we first heard it.
But it's true. This peace was no good.

1610
01:39:36,191 --> 01:39:37,704
It'll break any day now.

1611
01:39:37,791 --> 01:39:41,386
This self-styled Emperor
has made an alliance with Spain.

1612
01:39:41,471 --> 01:39:44,110
He's raked together a new fleet
from goodness knows where.

1613
01:39:44,191 --> 01:39:47,467
And he's building transports and barges
as fast as he can turn them out.

1614
01:39:47,551 --> 01:39:51,305
From Boulogne to Brest,
every single Channel port is chock-full of them.

1615
01:39:51,391 --> 01:39:54,667
He's got a whole army behind him
waiting to embark.

1616
01:39:54,751 --> 01:39:58,460
A few weeks from now,
all he'll need is a fair wind.

1617
01:39:59,471 --> 01:40:02,383
And all you'll need... will be Nelson.

1618
01:40:03,231 --> 01:40:04,630
Yes, that's it, my lady.

1619
01:40:05,671 --> 01:40:07,502
- Is that all?
- That's all, my lady.

1620
01:40:07,591 --> 01:40:09,547
You see...

1621
01:40:09,631 --> 01:40:11,110
Well...

1622
01:40:11,191 --> 01:40:13,227
Nelson's the only man who can save us.

1623
01:40:13,311 --> 01:40:14,585
Now, listen to me, Hardy,

1624
01:40:14,671 --> 01:40:18,380
I have helped the Navy whenever I could,
but not this time, Hardy, not this time.

1625
01:40:18,471 --> 01:40:22,623
Let them find some other man to take command.
Keith or Parker or St Vincent himself. Not him!

1626
01:40:22,711 --> 01:40:25,271
Don't they understand, Hardy?
He's given so much.

1627
01:40:25,351 --> 01:40:26,830
His arm, his sight, his health.

1628
01:40:26,911 --> 01:40:28,629
He needs rest and he must have it.

1629
01:40:28,711 --> 01:40:31,783
For the first time in his life
he's found peace of mind and happiness.

1630
01:40:31,871 --> 01:40:33,543
And I'm going to see that he keeps it.

1631
01:40:33,631 --> 01:40:35,462
If they want me to use my influence, I will.

1632
01:40:35,551 --> 01:40:39,590
All my influence to persuade him
that this new war is none of his business!

1633
01:40:42,151 --> 01:40:43,869
That's...

1634
01:40:43,951 --> 01:40:45,907
all I have to say.

1635
01:40:46,791 --> 01:40:51,069
Of course, there's nothing to prevent you from
talking it over with him personally at luncheon.

1636
01:40:52,271 --> 01:40:54,466
Will you stay?
No, thank you, my lady.

1637
01:40:54,551 --> 01:40:57,270
I think perhaps l'd better get back.

1638
01:40:59,031 --> 01:41:00,225
Goodbye, Hardy.

1639
01:41:07,511 --> 01:41:09,467
(Carriage withdraws)

1640
01:41:56,991 --> 01:42:00,461
Oh, come along. I thought you were dressing.
What have you been doing?

1641
01:42:00,551 --> 01:42:03,588
We'll never get there if you don't look sharp.
Besides, I'm hungry.

1642
01:42:03,671 --> 01:42:04,865
Starving.

1643
01:42:04,951 --> 01:42:06,942
I don't think we'll go today, Horatio.

1644
01:42:07,031 --> 01:42:11,707
It will save two trips if we pick her up tomorrow,
after you've been to the Admiralty.

1645
01:42:14,351 --> 01:42:15,830
The Admiralty?

1646
01:42:15,911 --> 01:42:17,663
Hardy has been here. They sent him.

1647
01:42:17,751 --> 01:42:19,707
They need you, dear, badly.

1648
01:42:19,791 --> 01:42:22,783
This war is coming, as you always said it would.

1649
01:42:22,871 --> 01:42:24,827
And there's no-one else.

1650
01:42:42,951 --> 01:42:44,907
Did you tell Hardy I would go?

1651
01:42:45,951 --> 01:42:47,907
Yes.

1652
01:42:48,831 --> 01:42:50,981
It's a matter of course, dear, isn't it?

1653
01:43:02,631 --> 01:43:05,748
It'll be freezing tonight on the high roads
over the downs.

1654
01:43:05,831 --> 01:43:08,186
Yes,
I think I'll take the little rug I use in my study.

1655
01:43:08,271 --> 01:43:11,104
- Oh, yes, I know, I'll get it.
- I'll get it, Mother.

1656
01:43:26,871 --> 01:43:28,827
(Carriage withdraws)

1657
01:43:36,031 --> 01:43:37,987
He thought he wouldn't need the rug.

1658
01:43:44,991 --> 01:43:46,947
He'll never come back, Mother.

1659
01:44:01,671 --> 01:44:04,902
? Cheer up, my lads,'tis to glory we steer

1660
01:44:05,471 --> 01:44:10,226
? To add something new to this wonderful year

1661
01:44:10,311 --> 01:44:14,384
? To honour we call you as free men not slaves

1662
01:44:14,471 --> 01:44:18,510
? For who are so free as the sons of the waves?

1663
01:44:18,591 --> 01:44:20,627
? Hearts of oak are our ships

1664
01:44:20,711 --> 01:44:22,667
? Jolly tars are our men

1665
01:44:23,511 --> 01:44:25,786
? We always are ready

1666
01:44:25,871 --> 01:44:27,827
? Steady, boys, steady

1667
01:44:28,351 --> 01:44:32,629
? We'll fight and we'll conquer again and again

1668
01:44:33,351 --> 01:44:36,070
Mr Pasco,
I will now amuse the fleet with a signal.

1669
01:44:36,831 --> 01:44:38,105
Mr Pasco,

1670
01:44:38,191 --> 01:44:40,147
I wish to say to the fleet...

1671
01:44:41,391 --> 01:44:43,859
..''England confides
that every man will do his duty.''

1672
01:44:43,951 --> 01:44:46,181
Be quick. I've one more to follow for close action.

1673
01:44:46,271 --> 01:44:49,308
If you will permit me to substitute
''expects'' for ''confides'',

1674
01:44:49,391 --> 01:44:50,665
it will be sooner completed.

1675
01:44:50,751 --> 01:44:52,707
That will do. Make it directly.

1676
01:44:53,751 --> 01:44:56,584
Those Frenchmen
have sharpshooters up in the rigging, sir.

1677
01:44:56,671 --> 01:44:57,820
I know. Why do you tell me?

1678
01:44:57,911 --> 01:45:01,586
Do you think it's wise to wear all those
decorations? They make a nice target.

1679
01:45:01,671 --> 01:45:03,866
- I won them in battle, didn't l?
- Yes, sir, but...

1680
01:45:03,951 --> 01:45:05,907
Then I shall wear them in battle.

1681
01:45:27,191 --> 01:45:28,021
England...

1682
01:45:35,591 --> 01:45:36,546
Expects...

1683
01:45:37,431 --> 01:45:38,466
That...

1684
01:45:39,351 --> 01:45:40,261
Every...

1685
01:45:41,271 --> 01:45:41,908
Man...

1686
01:45:43,551 --> 01:45:45,348
Will...

1687
01:45:45,431 --> 01:45:46,147
Do...

1688
01:45:47,391 --> 01:45:48,983
His...

1689
01:45:49,711 --> 01:45:50,666
Duty.

1690
01:45:50,751 --> 01:45:54,505
? Come cheer up, my lads,'tis to glory we sail

1691
01:45:54,591 --> 01:45:58,186
? To add something new to this wonderful year

1692
01:45:58,911 --> 01:46:03,302
? To honour we call you as free men not slaves

1693
01:46:03,391 --> 01:46:07,543
? For who are so free as the sons of the waves?

1694
01:46:07,631 --> 01:46:09,587
? Hearts of oak are our ships

1695
01:46:09,671 --> 01:46:11,787
? Jolly tars are our men

1696
01:46:12,631 --> 01:46:14,986
? We always are ready

1697
01:46:15,071 --> 01:46:17,949
? Steady, boys, steady

1698
01:46:18,031 --> 01:46:19,828
? We'll fight and we'll conquer...

1699
01:46:19,911 --> 01:46:21,867
We'll be on them in half an hour, sir.

1700
01:46:32,031 --> 01:46:34,750
Mon capitaine,
la flotte enemie est nord-ouest et bâbord.

1701
01:46:34,831 --> 01:46:37,550
Mon amiral,
la flotte enemie est nord-ouest et bâbord.

1702
01:46:37,631 --> 01:46:38,859
Prèparez pour l'attaque.

1703
01:46:58,191 --> 01:47:00,147
(Cannonfire)

1704
01:47:19,911 --> 01:47:22,220
- They're getting pretty close now, sir.
-Not yet.

1705
01:47:22,311 --> 01:47:23,221
(Explosions)

1706
01:47:58,431 --> 01:48:00,149
Starboard broadside fire as you bear.

1707
01:48:00,231 --> 01:48:02,620
(Repeats order)

1708
01:48:31,351 --> 01:48:33,228
(Man shouts)

1709
01:48:44,351 --> 01:48:46,581
(Cannonfire continues)

1710
01:49:26,951 --> 01:49:28,907
Voilà l'Amiral!

1711
01:49:35,951 --> 01:49:36,701
Sir!

1712
01:49:42,431 --> 01:49:44,228
They've... done for me, at last.

1713
01:49:44,311 --> 01:49:45,983
You're not badly hurt, are you, sir?

1714
01:49:46,071 --> 01:49:48,380
My backbone... shot through.

1715
01:49:48,471 --> 01:49:50,587
(Explosions)

1716
01:49:55,071 --> 01:49:58,507
HARDY: I'll carry you to Dr Beattie.
- You stay on deck. Come to me when you can.

1717
01:50:00,551 --> 01:50:02,587
Cover my face... these decorations.

1718
01:50:02,671 --> 01:50:05,344
No time for the men to see me like this.

1719
01:50:08,871 --> 01:50:10,827
(Explosions continue)

1720
01:50:40,991 --> 01:50:42,947
Mr Beattie...

1721
01:50:44,071 --> 01:50:46,949
... I have no feeling... below my breast.

1722
01:50:48,471 --> 01:50:50,427
No lower.

1723
01:50:50,511 --> 01:50:52,467
I know what that means, Mr Beattie.

1724
01:50:53,711 --> 01:50:55,110
My spine is broken.

1725
01:50:55,191 --> 01:50:57,466
My lord...unhappily for our country,

1726
01:50:57,551 --> 01:51:00,019
nothing...can be done for you.

1727
01:51:00,991 --> 01:51:02,947
Poor Emma.

1728
01:51:03,671 --> 01:51:05,627
What will become of her?

1729
01:51:23,871 --> 01:51:25,827
(Shouting from above deck)

1730
01:51:28,071 --> 01:51:29,220
Was that cheering?

1731
01:51:29,311 --> 01:51:31,188
They're cheering in all our ships, my lord.

1732
01:51:31,271 --> 01:51:33,262
The French line has broken.

1733
01:51:33,351 --> 01:51:35,307
Why doesn't Hardy come?

1734
01:51:35,391 --> 01:51:38,189
- He must be killed.
- He's on deck, sir. He can't leave.

1735
01:51:38,271 --> 01:51:40,227
(Shouting)

1736
01:51:58,071 --> 01:51:59,504
(Moans)

1737
01:51:59,591 --> 01:52:00,990
(Gasps)

1738
01:52:01,071 --> 01:52:03,027
They're cheering again.

1739
01:52:03,791 --> 01:52:05,861
The French flagship has surrendered, sir.

1740
01:52:06,711 --> 01:52:08,349
(Croakily ) Good.

1741
01:52:08,431 --> 01:52:09,989
Why don't they bring Hardy to me?

1742
01:52:10,071 --> 01:52:12,744
He sends a message, sir.
We're against the Redoubtable.

1743
01:52:12,831 --> 01:52:14,901
When we have beaten her, he will come.

1744
01:52:14,991 --> 01:52:16,947
(Nelson gasps)

1745
01:52:50,951 --> 01:52:53,545
- How goes it, Hardy?
- Fourteen of them are ours, sir.

1746
01:52:55,071 --> 01:52:56,902
Not enough.

1747
01:52:56,991 --> 01:52:59,266
Twenty. Twenty.

1748
01:53:09,271 --> 01:53:12,900
(Gasps) Don't throw me overboard, Hardy.

1749
01:53:12,991 --> 01:53:15,710
No, sir.
You know what to do.

1750
01:53:17,111 --> 01:53:20,660
Let my dear Lady Hamilton have my hair...

1751
01:53:21,751 --> 01:53:23,389
..and all things belonging to me.

1752
01:53:23,471 --> 01:53:26,190
You mustn't die, sir. You mustn't die!

1753
01:53:27,231 --> 01:53:29,142
(Softly ) It's all over now, Hardy.

1754
01:53:29,231 --> 01:53:31,187
All over now.

1755
01:53:32,711 --> 01:53:34,144
(Whispers)

1756
01:53:34,231 --> 01:53:35,425
Sir!

1757
01:53:35,511 --> 01:53:38,423
Sir! It's eighteen now sir

1758
01:53:39,711 --> 01:53:41,861
Eighteen - a great victory.

1759
01:53:46,071 --> 01:53:48,027
Thank God.

1760
01:53:49,071 --> 01:53:51,027
I have done my duty.

1761
01:53:54,191 --> 01:53:56,830
Kiss me...Hardy.

1762
01:54:20,431 --> 01:54:23,468
I am the resurrection and the life,
sayeth the Lord.

1763
01:54:23,551 --> 01:54:28,147
He that believeth in me
though he were dead, yet shall he live;

1764
01:54:28,231 --> 01:54:31,621
And whosoever liveth and believeth in me
shall never die.

1765
01:54:32,911 --> 01:54:34,867
(Continues sermon)

1766
01:55:11,711 --> 01:55:14,783
It's all right, Anna, I'll draw them myself.
Thank you.

1767
01:55:51,591 --> 01:55:53,024
My lady.

1768
01:55:53,111 --> 01:55:56,387
- Do you come from Portsmouth, Hardy?
-No, Spithead, Lady Hamilton.

1769
01:55:56,471 --> 01:55:58,621
I came on the St George, she's our fastest ship.

1770
01:55:58,711 --> 01:56:02,181
Captain Blackwood went ahead to London
with the news.

1771
01:56:02,271 --> 01:56:04,227
What is the news, Hardy?

1772
01:56:04,991 --> 01:56:08,347
It was a great victory.
It was the greatest we've ever known.

1773
01:56:09,071 --> 01:56:11,027
That's wonderful.

1774
01:56:12,591 --> 01:56:14,309
It was nine days ago...

1775
01:56:15,631 --> 01:56:20,068
we engaged them off Cape Trafalgar
the combined fleets of France and Spain

1776
01:56:22,271 --> 01:56:24,227
They've been destroyed

1777
01:56:25,351 --> 01:56:28,900
The oceans are free once more
and England is safe from invasion

1778
01:56:33,551 --> 01:56:37,464
The first cannon was fired a little after twelve

1779
01:56:38,631 --> 01:56:42,226
Within one hour five French
ships-of-the-line had struck their flags

1780
01:56:42,311 --> 01:56:44,108
His plan was magnificent

1781
01:56:44,191 --> 01:56:47,467
He swung our fleet from line of battle
into two spearheads,

1782
01:56:47,551 --> 01:56:50,304
that broke the enemy line
into three separate parts.

1783
01:56:51,191 --> 01:56:51,987
Then...

1784
01:56:53,751 --> 01:56:57,790
about one-thirty
I was walking with him on the upper deck

1785
01:56:59,871 --> 01:57:01,304
The fighting was at its height

1786
01:57:01,391 --> 01:57:04,224
The French flagship the Redoubtable
came through the smoke

1787
01:57:04,311 --> 01:57:07,269
and we fought alongside one another

1788
01:57:07,351 --> 01:57:09,307
he was so

1789
01:57:09,391 --> 01:57:11,268
confident.

1790
01:57:12,351 --> 01:57:14,945
We'd just...turned to go...back to the...

1791
01:57:15,871 --> 01:57:18,101
(Sobs)

1792
01:57:31,991 --> 01:57:33,947
By sunset

1793
01:57:34,031 --> 01:57:35,987
everything was over

1794
01:57:37,391 --> 01:57:38,426
But

1795
01:57:38,511 --> 01:57:41,867
he he lived to know
he'd won England's greatest victory

1796
01:57:44,951 --> 01:57:47,863
His His last thoughts were with you my lady

1797
01:57:49,471 --> 01:57:51,826
That you should be cared for

1798
01:57:55,711 --> 01:57:57,667
(Sobs softly )

1799
01:58:13,071 --> 01:58:15,027
(Door slams)

1800
01:59:11,071 --> 01:59:14,143
- And then?
- Then what?

1801
01:59:14,231 --> 01:59:16,187
What happened after?

1802
01:59:20,951 --> 01:59:22,907
There is no then.

1803
01:59:24,311 --> 01:59:26,461
There is no after.
